<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, U.S. Must Do More to Help Asia Out of Crisis: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) has urged
Japan and the United States to do more to help stabilize the
troubled Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the Asia Australia Institute in Sydney Sunday
night, the visiting chief executive said Japan, as the largest
economy in Asia and the second largest in the world, "must do more
to help stabilize the region by maintaining positive growth and
stability in the yen."
</P>
<P>
"The recent dramatic fall in the value of the yen is very
damaging, not just to Asia but to the economy around the world,"
Tung told a high-powered audience of about 200 businessmen and
politicians, including former prime ministers G. Whitlam and Bob
Hawke.
</P>
<P>
"I know we in Hong Kong and the leaders in Beijing have been
urged by many around the world to maintain stability of our
currencies," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There needs to be similar urgency in stabilizing the yen," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to economic stimulus packages, the Japanese
Government must urgently come out with credible policies in the
reform and liberalization of her banking sector," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The (Asian) financial crisis cannot be solved by official
funds alone. The IMF (International Monetary Fund) must provide
funding and conditionality, in combination with voluntary
rollovers by private sector banks."
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, there is still U.S. legislative reluctance to
provide capital to the IMF."
</P>
<P>
"Now is not the time not to provide adequate water to the
global fireman," he said.
</P>
<P>
On other essential conditions for an Asian recovery from the
current crisis, Tung said, "there must be clear signs that the
Asian economies are generating trade surpluses, instead of
deficits."
</P>
<P>
He said the stability of the (Chinese currency) Renminbi and
the Hong Kong dollar must be maintained as the anchors of currency
stability in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"No one should doubt the tremendous sacrifice that both Hong
Kong and the mainland of China are bearing to prevent the problems
of currency depreciation from escalating," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said: "everyone in Asia must press ahead with reforms to cut
out the inefficiencies and post-bubble effects that led to the
Asian crisis".
</P>
<P>
Tung, who arrived in Australia Sunday morning for a three-day
visit to Sydney and Melbourne, also spoke about how Hong Kong had
coped with the turmoil through its strong financial position, the
determination to defend the HK-U.S. dollar link.
</P>
<P>
During his address, the chief Executive also briefed the
audience about Hong Kong's first year as a Special Administrative
Region of China, and the successful implementation of the "One
Country, Two Systems" concept.
</P>
<P>
Tung is scheduled to meet Australian Prime Minister John
Howard, Deputy Prime Minister and Trade Minister Tim Fischer,
Finance Minister John Fahey and some state government leaders.
</P>
<P>
Tung will end his visit to Australia on Wednesday and fly from
Melbourne to New Zealand for a three-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
