<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hamas Refuses Offer to Join PNA Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Hamas founder and spiritual
leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin has turned down an offer to join the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA), Hamas leaders in Gaza were
quoted as saying Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Media and Communication Center (JMCC), an East
Jerusalem-based Palestinian news service, reported that Yassin
announced his rejection Sunday in Sudan, where he is waiting for
Israeli permission to return to Gaza from a regional tour.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Sunday, a Palestinian officials confirmed to Xinhua
that PNA President Yasser Arafat has asked Hamas - the militant
Islamic Resistance Movement - to join the PNA Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
To have political talks with the PNA is one thing, Yassin said,
but to join the PNA cabinet is not in line with Hamas policy.
</P>
<P>
The JMCC quoted unnamed Hamas leaders in Gaza as saying that
Yassin would inform Arafat at a scheduled meeting next week of his
decision.
</P>
<P>
Hamas strongly opposes the Oslo peace accords signed between
Israel and the Arafat-led Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO),
and has launched scores of suicide bombings in Israel since the
current Israeli-Palestinian peace process began in 1993.
</P>
<P>
It has rejected previous offers to join the PNA self-rule
government and boycotted Palestinian elections in 1996, stressing
that its only goal is to destroy Israel through armed struggle.
</P>
<P>
PNA Cabinet Secretary Tayeb Abdel Rahim clarified in Gaza
Sunday that Hamas and other Palestinian political parties are
invited to hold consultations only on the current political
developments in the territories, not on their participation in the
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will start a four-day dialogue next Tuesday with leaders
of other political factions to discuss national reconciliation and
the peace process. The PLO's Executive Committee will later
evaluate the results of such consultations, Rahim said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will listen to the parties' comments and views on the
PNA's past performance, future improvement of the PNA work, as
well as the planned reshuffle of PNA Cabinet, he added.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has forwarded Arafat's request to the Hamas officials
in Gaza on Saturday, saying Arafat planned to meet Hamas leaders
as part of a wide-ranging effort across the Palestinian political
spectrum on forming a new government.
</P>
<P>
Arafat agreed at a meeting of the PLO Executive Committee in
Gaza on Thursday to shuffle his cabinet. The decision came days
ahead of a June 15 deadline set by the Palestinian Legislative
Council (PLC) for Arafat to reform his administration over alleged
corruption and misrule or face a no-confidence vote in the PLC.
</P>
<P>
Arafat requested on Saturday the PLC to delay the no-confidence
vote for 10 days to allow him time for broad talks on reshuffling
his Cabinet, which PLO officials said could take place on June
25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
