<HEADLINE> GCC Oil Ministers to Meet For Oil Price Hikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Oil ministers of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) member states will gather in Saudi
capital Riyadh Tuesday to discuss ways of bolstering oil prices,
GCC General Secretariat announced Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming meeting comes amid moves by members and
non-members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC) to slash oil production to shore up prices on world markets.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will assess the current situation and decide what
measures will be taken accordingly in view of another round of oil
production cut spearheaded by Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and non-OPEC
Mexico, reported Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The three countries clinched a deal on June 4 to further slash
their output by 450,000 barrels per day (bpd) from July 1 to
improve the still sluggish oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Their first try was a deal in March to reduce their production
in order to trim world oil supply by 1.6 million to 2 million bpd
as oil prices slumped to a nine-year low.
</P>
<P>
The move was followed by the OPEC decision to cut 1.25 million
bpd starting from April 1 till the end of the year. But the world
market was little moved by the cut.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance, groups six
Arab countries - Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain, Qatar, Oman and
the United Arab Emirates - whose economy depends heavily on oil
earnings.
</P>
<P>
The GCC ministers will also discuss a string of joint projects,
including natural gas network, and explore ways to boost gas trade
with European Union member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
