<HEADLINE> Iraq, UNSCOM Hold Two Rounds of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) held another two rounds of talks on Sunday in
a bid to work out a program of priority tasks that Iraq should
fulfill before the sanctions can be lifted.
</P>
<P>
The two sides had held two rounds of talks on Saturday, but
both sides refused to comment on the outcome of their talks.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz and UNSCOM Chairman
Richard Butler headed their respective teams during these
talks. No details are available.
</P>
<P>
Butler arrived here Thursday and will leave on Monday. He said
at Thursday's press conference that Iraq has not provided adequate
information on its biological weapons program and that access to
information will be the main task for Iraq to fulfill.
</P>
<P>
However, Iraqi National Assembly (parliament) Speaker Saadoun
Hammadi on Saturday accused UNSCOM of pursuing a procrastination
policy, warning that U.N. inspections in Iraq would not be
endless, and that they would be resisted by Iraqi people and all
Arabs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
