<HEADLINE> Funeral Procession for Young Iraqi Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 14 (Xinhua) -- A funeral procession was held
Sunday for 43 Iraqi children who died as a result of food and
medicine shortages arising from the U.N. sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Head of Iraqi Association for Children Support, Sultan
Ash-Shawi, told reporters that over 1.5 million Iraqis, mostly
children, have died since the sanctions began seven years ago
after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Ash-Shawi urged the international community to work for
lifting the sanctions to bring an end to Iraqi people's sufferings.
</P>
<P>
A memo of protest, addressed in the name of bereaved families
to the U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, denounced as "vicious
crime" against Iraqi children the U.S. action to keep the
sanctions in place.
</P>
<P>
People from all walks of life, including religious dignitaries,
took part in the funeral.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics released by Iraqi Health
Ministry, nearly 5,000 Iraqi children under age five died in May
due to severe shortages of food and medicine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
