<HEADLINE> U.S. Official Stresses Boosting Palestinian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. official said
here Sunday that improving the economic situation in the
Palestinian self-rule areas is good for the regional stability.
</P>
<P>
Before meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
United States Undersecretary of State for Economic Affairs Stuart
Eizenstat stressed that a better economic situation in the
territories is also in line with the security interests of Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. feels the Palestinian economy is "on the
rise" since more Palestinians have been allowed to work in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said about 110,000 legal and illegal Palestinian
laborers are currently working in Israel. Every year, the
Palestinian workers inject millions of dollars into the fledgling
Palestinian economy, which is dominated by Israel and often
suffers from Israeli closure of the borders.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu rejected the charges that Israel has restrained
the economic growth of the Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
He said his government has made efforts to help the
Palestinians advance their economy, noting that the year 1998 is
expected to be the best year for the economic growth in the
Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat, who arrived in Israel on Friday, will discuss with
Netanyahu the economic development in the region. He is also
expected to update Netanyahu on his latest report regarding the
Jewish gold, which was plundered by the Nazis and laundered in
Switzerland in World War II. 
</P>
</TEXT>
