<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Returns to World Soccer Stage with Win over Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAINT-ETIENNE, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia returned to the World
Cup finals here on Sunday with a 1-0 win over Iran in Group F after
being left for six years in soccer wilderness.
</P>
<P>
Sinisa Mihajlovic, a free kick expert who plays for Italian club
Sampdoria, blasted a curvy, booming free kick from 25 meters towards
the goal 28 minutes into the second half.
</P>
<P>
Iranian goaltender Nima Nakisa dived in the right direction but
could not stop the ball flying into the bottom of net.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Ali Daei, with German Bundesliga side Arminia Bielefeld,
almost equalized with a header in the 41st minute but the ball was
captured by Yugoslavian keeper Ivica Kralj.
</P>
<P>
The two teams played totally different styles, with the Yugoslavs
advancing slowly looking for killing shots and the Iranians featuring
speedy counter-attacks masterminded by playmaker Mehdi Mahdavikia.
</P>
<P>
Defender Goran Djorovic nearly opened account for the Balkan nation
when his 15th-minute header hit the bar and another from midfielder
Slavisa Jokanovic in the 29th minute also brought scare to Nakisa
before soaring over the bar.
</P>
<P>
But after the opening 30 minutes, the Yugoslva offences were almost
totally thwarted by a well-organized Iranian defence, which heavily
marked Predrag Mijatovic of Real Madrid.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia had been left out in soccer wilderness for six years
because of civil strifes, missing the last two European Championships
in 1992 and 1996, and the last World Cup finals in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian referee Alberto Tejada Noriega showed yellow cards to
Yugoslavia's Zeljko Petrovic and captain Dragan Stojkovic during the
game held in Stade Geoffroy-Guichard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
