<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Erekat Urges Pressure to Stop Israel's Illegal Acts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian chief negotiator
Saeb Erekat has called on the parties concerned to pressure Israel
to stop all its illegal acts that could further devastate the
deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
Erekat made this call in a letter sent Sunday from Cairo to
Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh, U.S. peace envoy Dennis
Ross, European Union peace envoy Miguel Moratinos, U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan and a number of European and Asian leaders,
according to Jerusalem-based Palestinian news service JMCC.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Erekat, also minister of local government of
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA), said that the illegal
Israeli actions in land confiscation, home demolition and murder
of Palestinians will have serious repercussions that would further
harm the deadlocked Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Israel to revoke the decisions to form armed
militias in the settlements and the declaration Thursday to
upgrade the settlement of Ariel, located between Ramallah and
Nablus in the West Bank, into a city.
</P>
<P>
Several Palestinians have recently been stabbed to death in
East Jerusalem and other settlements. Since the beginning of this
month Israeli forces have demolished 34 Palestinan houses in the
PNA-controlled areas and East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
All these acts are considered as a dangerous development,
Erekat said in his letter.
</P>
<P>
All these activities were planned by the Israeli government for
the purpose of destroying the peace process and the international
community must intervene immediately, he said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Army Central Commander Uzi Dayan signed an order
Thursday for setting up civilian guards at Jewish settlements in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip to ensure the safety of the
settlers. Such forces will be operational within the next few
weeks first at the larger settlements including Ariel.
</P>
<P>
Erekat was in Cairo, accompanying PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat on
his visit to Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
