<HEADLINE> Iran, Austria to Forge Broad Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Austria signed a
memorandum of understanding Sunday to enhance economic
cooperation, the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Industry Minister Gholamreza Shafei and Austrian
Minister of Economics Johann Farnleitner oversaw the signing of
the memo.
</P>
<P>
Under the memo, Iranian Pars Wagon Company and Austrian Firm of
Siemens will launch a joint venture to produce auto parts, wagons,
trams and trains.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will jointly invest in cement, electricity,
paper and oil refining industries, projects to improve drinking
water and semi-conductor research, according to the memo.
</P>
<P>
They will also enhance cooperation in agriculture, forestry,
urban construction, natural disaster prevention in line with the
memo.
</P>
<P>
Austria has agreed to help facilitate Iran's non-oil exports to
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Farnleitner, who is here for Iran-Austria joint economic
commission, held talks Sunday with Iranian Minister of Roads and
Transport Mahmoud Hojjati to discuss ways for cooperation in
transportation.
</P>
<P>
Hojjati said Tehran was ready to cooperate with Austria in air,
land and sea transport, and hoped that the two countries can join
hands in producing cars and spare parts for passenger trains, and
rail tracks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
