<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Women to Fight Domestic Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Media Women's
Association (TAMWA) will hold a week-long course on domestic
violence against women in Dar es Salaam starting Monday.
</P>
<P>
The course has come at a time when domestic violence cases
have increased tremendously, said the TAMWA Director Leila Sheikh
Hashim over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Hashim told the press in the city that 80 representatives from
TAMWA-run victim centers will take part in the course. It will be
opened by ambassador Gertrude Mongella, a well-known woman
activist.
</P>
<P>
According to a research made by TAMWA, the number of clients
in the centers have increased from an average of 30 to 120.
</P>
<P>
She said TAMWA plans to mobilize communities all over the
country to establish victim centers which will be responsible for
offering legal and other assistances to victims of domestic
violence.
</P>
<P>
TAMWA has assisted more than 180 victims of domestic violence
since September 1997. A survey conducted by the organization
shows that over the last six years, there were 1,992 reported
cases of domestic violence in the form of battery, threats and
use of abusive language.
</P>
<P>
A United States expert on gender violence and victim support
Colleen McGrath will facilitate the training program.
</P>
<P>
The course is funded by the United States Information Services
(USIS). 
</P>
</TEXT>
