<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM to Visit U.S. on Israeli Pullout Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri is to pay an official visit to the United States Monday, to
focus on the Israeli proposal for a conditional withdrawal from
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Hariri will hold talks with U.S. President
Bill Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright over the
lastest developments in the region, especially the Israeli offer,
the Orient Radio here reported.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Israel decided to endorse for the first time in two
decades the United Nations resolution 425 calling for it to
withdraw troops from south Lebanon. But it conditioned the pullout
on Lebanese government's cooperation in security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 1,100-square-kilometer border strip in
southern Lebanon as the so-called Security Zone in 1985 in an
attempt to prevent cross-border guerrilla attacks. Anti-Israeli
guerrilla forces, especially the Iranian-backed Hezbollah (Party
of God), have been fighting to oust the Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon flatly rejected the Israeli offer, insisting that the
withdrawal must be carried out unconditionally as stipulated in
the U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and the U.N. have welcomed the Israeli offer,
describing it as a "positive step" toward a resolution of the
long-running south Lebanon occupation.
</P>
<P>
Albright has also sent a message to Lebanese Foreign Minister
Fares Boueiz, urging Beirut to positively consider the Israeli
offer.
</P>
<P>
Hariri's visit to the U.S. is part of an international campaign
launched jointly by Lebanon and its powerful ally Syria to
confront so-called Israeli "manoeuvre."
</P>
<P>
Boueiz has already summoned ambassadors of the five permanent
members of the U.N. Security Council in Beirut to explain
Lebanon's stance on rejecting the Israeli withdrawal offer.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which has 40,000 troops deployed as peacekeepers in
Lebanon, is seeking a comprehensive deal which demands a
simultaneous Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights captured
from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in the U.S., Hariri will also go to New York to
meet U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to discuss the Israeli
pullout plan as well as Lebanon's position in the stalled Middle
East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
