<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vitamin K Exerts Cancer-Killing Effects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Scientists at the University of
Pittsburgh have discovered how a novel form of vitamin K can exert
its cancer-killing effects in primary liver cancers, according to
The Journal of Biological Chemistry.
</P>
<P>
"One of the attractive features of this unique compound is that
it appears to stop cancer cell growth without producing toxicity.
We now are testing this compound against cancers in rats, and
given positive results, we hope to begin clinical trials of this
agent within two years," said Brian Carr, professor and director
of the Liver Center at the University of Pittsburgh Cancer
Institute.
</P>
<P>
The Pittsburgh research team found that a vitamin K analog, Cpd
5 blocks the activity of an important group of enzymes called
protein-tyrosine phosphatases inside liver cancer cells. These
enzymes normally add small molecules called phosphate groups to
selected proteins inside cells. The altered proteins, called
tyrosine phosphorylated proteins, are known to trigger a variety
of activities within cells. They exert anti-cancer effects but
inducing the shutdown and subsequent death of a cell, commonly
referred to as programmed cell death.
</P>
<P>
Liver cancer is thought to be one of the three commonest
cancers worldwide. The disease caused about 15,000 U.S. death in
1997 alone. Major causes of this cancer include infection with
either hepatitis B or C or chronic alcohol consumption.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
