will "fight to the last", said head coach Jalal Talebi here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We played a fair game and did our best," said Talebi. "There was
nothing shameful in this game for us."
</P>
<P>
"Our mission is not finished, we have to play against the United
States and Germany ahd we know they will be hard games," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Each game has a different meaning for us but we will fight to a
standstill. If we are going to go down, then we will go down fighting.
We will fight to the last," Talebi said.
</P>
<P>
Talebi standed by goalkeeper Nima Nakisa, saying he was happy with
his goalie overall.
</P>
<P>
"He is still very young and if we lost today it was because of the
inexperience throughout the team not just him," Talebi said.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav coach Slobodan Santrac was not satisfied with the team's
performance despite the victory on a free kick converted by Sinisa
Mihajlovic in the 73rd minute.
</P>
<P>
"I am happy with the fact that we won but I am not satisfied with
the performance of my team," he said. "Before the game I told my
players that Iran was a strong side but nobody believed me."
</P>
<P>
He added, "Iran played exactly as we expected them to but my
players did not do what they ought to have done."
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavian player Slavisa Jokanovic said, "It was a very difficult
game, they defended very, very tightly and it was difficult to ge
through. We were really lucky to get these three points." 
</P>
