<HEADLINE> Burundi Factions Delegates Arrive for Arusha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ARUSHA, Tanzania, June 14 (Xinhua)-- The Burundi government
and the opposition factions, for the first time since Major
Pierre Buyoya took power two years ago, sent delegates
here on Sunday afternoon to take part in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni, Rwandan President Pasteur
Bizimungu, and Zambian Vice President Christon Tembo also led
their delegations to attend the opening session of the talks
scheduled for Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Burundi delegation said that some 50
delegates had came here from Bujumbura.
</P>
<P>
"President Buyoya will come here tomorrow morning for the
meeting," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian officials said that Heads of State and Government
from Kenya, the Democratic Republic of Congo and Ethiopia as well
as from the host Tanzania will also be present at the session to
be held in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks will be hosted by Tanzania's former President
Julius Nyerere, who has been facilitating the conflicts between
the Burundi government and the oppositions since July 1996 when
the above mentioned seven east and central African countries
imposed economic sanctions on Bujumbura after Major Buyoya
toppled a civilian government led by President Sylvester
Ntibantunganya.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, Nyerere met in Dar es Salaam separately with
all the Burundi factions leaders including the Speaker of the
National Assembly Leonce Ngendaknmana, former Presidents
Jean-Baptiste Bagaza and Ntibantunganya, chairman of the Front
pour la Democratie an Burundi (FRODEBU) Jean Minani, and Chairman
of the National Council for Defense and Democracy (CNDD) Leonard
Nyangoma as well as Buyoya.
</P>
<P>
They discussed all the preparations for the Arusha peace
talks, whose success may lead to an early lifting of the economic
sanctions on Burundi which has been imposed since August, 1966.
</P>
<P>
As a gesture to the calls by sanctions imposers to ease the
internal tension, Buyoya, an ethnic Tutsi, signed a new
transitional constitution, and named two vice presidents
including an ethnic Hutu leader of the main opposition party last
week, to replace the original premier.
</P>
<P>
More than 150,000 people, mostly civilians, have died in
bloody conflicts between the ethnic Hutu majority and the ruling
Tutsi minority since the assassination of Melchior Ndadaye, the
first president elected under a multiparty system in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
