<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Butler to Brief Kuwaiti Leaders on Talks with Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Chief U.N. weapons inspector
Richard Butler arrived here Monday to brief Kuwaiti leaders on the
results of his mission with Iraq, Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, Butler said "We have just come from very
important talks in Baghdad," during which he and Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz agreed to a two-month work program as
"concrete steps" toward freeing Baghdad from U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"I look forward to the opportunity to inform the senior
officials of the Kuwaiti government of what happened in these
talks and where we might go next," said Butler, chairman of the
United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) on disarming Iraq of
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on an Iraqi statement that visiting Kuwait was not
in his mandate, Butler said "Kuwait is a member state of the
United Nations and has an interest in the matter. It is completely
normal that I should come here and discuss these issues with
Kuwaiti government officials."
</P>
<P>
During his one-day visit here, Butler is scheduled to meet
Tuesday with the Kuwaiti Amir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah,
Crown Prince and Prime Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Salem
Al-Sabah, and Parliament Speaker Ahmed Abdul Aziz Al-Sadoun.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Iraq and UNSCOM agreed to lay down a two-month
timetable to end U.N. disarmament activities in Iraq, a big stride
toward the lifting of the U.N. economic sanctions imposed on Iraq
seven years ago after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
After their talks, Butler and Aziz told reporters that the two
sides would work together in the next two months and meet again in
early August to consider where they were up to.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and UNSCOM had been in a tug-of-war over weapons
inspections, which touched off a string of crises in the Gulf
region.
</P>
<P>
Iraq claims it has destroyed all the banned weapons in
compliance with the U.N. resolutions. But UNSCOM believes Baghdad
has not yet come clean in the areas of long-range missiles,
chemical and biological weapons, which dashed Iraq's hope to ease
the sanction when it was reviewed by the U.N. Security Council in
May.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council will allow the lifting of the
sanctions only after UNSCOM certifies that Iraq has scrapped all
its prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
Butler arrived in Baghdad last Thursday with a list of
obligations, known as "road map," that Iraq should fulfill, to
begin a fresh round of talks with Iraqi government.
</P>
<P>
Butler is due to deliver a regular report about his mission in
Iraq to the Security Council in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
