<HEADLINE> Attention: Correction: India to Continue its Efforts to Resume Talks With Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 15 (Xinhua) -- An External Affairs Ministry
spokesman said here Monday that India would continue its efforts
to resume talks with Pakistan to resolve outstanding issues
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Replying to question on the rejection of New Delhi's proposal
to hold foreign secretary level talks here on June 22 by
Islamabad, the spokesman said that India had made a "sincere
offer" to Pakistan for resuming bilateral talks in keeping with
the approach that a broad-based and sustained dialogue could
resolve outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
Differences over modalities on mainly how to discuss the
Kashmir issue, the major dispute between India and Pakistan, at
the foreign secretary level's talks had created a stalemate last
Friday with Islamabad rejecting New Delhi's proposal for
resumption of talks here on June 22 and instead inviting Indian
foreign secretary to Pakistan for the dialogue on June 20.
</P>
<P>
The Indo-Pak talks had come to a standstill twice in 1994 and
1997 over the dispute of Kashmir issue. India has time and again
claimed that Kashmir is a part of its territory and it could not
be talked over while Pakistan maintained that the Kashmir issue is
a main dispute between the two countries. The ties of the two
countries could not be improved unless the Kashmir issue is
resolved.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, a Pakistan high commission spokesman here
described as "pure speculation" a press report that the Pakistan
government would reduce its staff strength by 50 percent by the
first week of next month as part of an austerity drive to ward off
economic sanctions following its nuclear tests on May 28 and 30.
</P>
