<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Vows No Yielding on National Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu vowed on Monday that nothing can change his positions on
issues concerning Israel's security and interests in dealing with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that he is seeking a "total package" with the
Palestinians on the next troop redeployment in the West Bank and
further steps to advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks while talking to reporters at his
office after signing economic and telecommunications agreements
with visiting Bulgarian Foreign Minister Nadejda Nikolova, who
arrived here Sunday for a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Asked about his reaction to Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's
comments that he had "lost faith" in him, Netanyahu said he did
not mind what people says about him when it comes to the national
interests and security. He stressed that he would not change his
positions on those matters just because of other people's words.
</P>
<P>
Receiving Israeli opposition Labor Party's leader Ehud Barak in
Cairo Monday, Mubarak said that he has "received a lot of
promises" from Netanyahu but none of them has been fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak warned that if Israel can not reach an agreement on the
second redeployment with the Palestinians, the region could plunge
into a crisis. He urged Netanyahu to advance the peace process if
Israel does not want to damage the Israeli-Egyptian relations.
</P>
<P>
On the stalled talks on the second redeployment, Netanyahu said
the negotiations are focusing on a "total package" which would
combine the second and third stages of further withdrawal, and the
"Palestinian compliance with their obligations."
</P>
<P>
These echoed his remarks last week that the second pullback
agreement, if there is one, would be "the last agreement Israel
signs before the final status talks."
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Netanyahu has proposed combining the second
and third redeployment into a 15 percent troop withdrawal and then
entering into the permanent talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians interpreted Netanyahu's proposal as an attempt
to cancel or minimize the third redeployment which is stipulated
in the Hebron agreement signed in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. has been urging Israel to accept a 13 percent
withdrawal in the second redeployment, Netanyahu's idea means that
the scope of the third pullback will be only 2 percent, which is
regarded by the Palestinian side as too marginal to be accepted.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the Israeli-Bulgarian relations, Netanyahu said
he is "very happy" to watch the successful reforms being
carried out in Bulgaria and he "sees no dispute" between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Nikolova expressed her satisfaction over bilateral relations,
saying she came to Israel to strengthen the traditional ties and
establish a partnership between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
