<HEADLINE> Marseille Has Two Battle Fields at the Same Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The southern French metropolis of
Marseille is having two battlefields Monday afternoon: One at the
Velodrome Stadium where the English football team is playing their
Tunisian counterpart, another outside the stadium between the fans
of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Police had to use tear gas grenades to disperse the fans, after
they began fighting violently in front of a giant screen
transmitting live the match, in which England led 1-0 in first
half.
</P>
<P>
Sick of the rude behavior of English fans Sunday night, angry
Marseillese shouted to the elite CRS anti-riot police: "Kill
them. Tonight, they will put you on fire."
</P>
<P>
The new fighting broke out after the English footballers scored
their first goal.
</P>
<P>
The fans began throwing iron bars, beer bottles and benches at
each other in front of the screen on the Prado beach, where about
1,000 people were watching the game.
</P>
<P>
Sixty CRS policement intervened and took positions to separate
the fans into two different parts on a grass land near the beach.
</P>
<P>
A fan carrying Tunisian national flag was questioned by police.
</P>
<P>
Several other smaller scale skirmishes also took place on the
beach between the English and Tunisian fans.
</P>
<P>
At least 37 people were injured when violent fightings took
place between the fans of the two countries from Sunday night
till early Monday morning on the river side of the port city of
Marseille, where live a great North African community.
</P>
<P>
The French Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement said that
France will put everything into work to guarantee security during
the World Cup season. 
</P>
