<HEADLINE> European Leaders Begin EU Summit in Cardiff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARDIFF, Britain, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from the 15
European Union (EU) countries began their summit in Cardiff,
Britain, on Monday morning focusing on reforms to revitalize the
15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair, who chaired the two-day
summit, told reporters that the Cardiff summit was designed to
produce a "genuine debate" on the EU's future.
</P>
<P>
"There is a growing consensus to say that the (European) Union
has no choice but to change if it wants to make a success of the
single currency and enlargement, if it wants to take on the
competition in global markets," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
The main task at Cardiff was to prepare the EU "for the
opportunities and challenges of the next century", Blair's
official spokesman told a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders would recommend broad economic guidelines and
discuss promoting employment and growth, as well as completing the
single market and encouraging small businesses, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
They would also discuss EU enlargement and institutional
reforms, and were expected to exchange views on the worsening
crisis in Kosovo, the Middle East peace process and the
international financial situation. 
</P>
