<HEADLINE> French Prime Minister to Visit U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
will pay a three-day official visit to the United States from
Wednesday in a bid to boost his international profile.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic offensive is being launched because so little
known in the United States since he took up the post under
President Jacques Chirac a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Jospin will be received by President Bill Clinton on Thursday
at the White House, and will hold talks with Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
He will meet with the French community in Washington, speaker
of the House of Representatives Newt Gingrich, senators, Chairman
of the Federal Reserve Board Alan Greenspan, Secretary of Treasury
Robert Rubin, and President of the International Monetary Fund
Michel Camdessus.
</P>
<P>
Jospin will also meet with U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan in
New York on Friday before ending his official visit.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister will explain to U.S. leaders the economic
and social policy implemented over the past year by his
government, which was viewed with scepticism in the U.S. media
because of its strong leftwing flavor.
</P>
<P>
Jospin will tell U.S. leaders that, in general, France shares
the same values as the United States, so it is important for them
to keep their relations on the right track.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to discuss the situation in Kosovo and the
recent nuclear tests by India and Pakistan, as well as bilateral
cooperation in environmental protection and peace-keeping missions
in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine, Minister of
Finance and Economy Dominique Strauss-Kahn, and Minister of
National Education Claude Allegre, the French prime minister will
also open the first session of the joint French-U.S. Commission
which includes business leaders of the two countries. 
</P>
