<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Shortage Becoming Serious in Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 15 (Xinhua) -- A serious food shortage is
affecting five regions in southern Somalia at the end of the
rainy season, a local organization said Monday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the United Somalia Farmers Salvation, said
here Monday that the regions worst affected by famine and food
shortage are Bay, Bakol, Hiran, Middle and Lower Shabelle where
armed clashes, serious floods and less water have devastated the
crops of the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Abdurahman Sidow Abdi, said that more than 60
percent of the farms have been destroyed by last year's unusual
heavy rains and floods after the two main rivers in Somalia had
destroyed 60,000 hectares of farmlands and all major food
reservoirs in Bay, Lower and Middle Jubba regions.
</P>
<P>
Unless something is done, Abdi said, the emerging food
shortage will bring about a general famine and the people will
detract from the main Somalia's economy generating resources of
farming and livestock.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the international community, non-governmental
organizations and the United Nations agencies to come out for
assisting the helpless Somali farmers.
</P>
<P>
Abdi said that less than 50 percent of the farmlands in
southern Somalia was cultivated this season after the water
levels of the rivers had lowered while hundreds of other small
and rain-fed farms were devastated by rats which exhumed the
sowed seeds.
</P>
<P>
The farmers who produce about 80 percent of Somalia's
essential crops such as the maize, sorghum and sesame are now on
the brink of total starvation and famine, following their
displacement by floods, or less water and plague of rats, said
Abdi.
</P>
<P>
The regional governor of Middle Shabelle, Nur Mohamed Shirbow,
confirmed last week that serious famine has hit his region.
</P>
<P>
The Rahanwein Resistance Army (RRA) said three people died for
famine near the town of Baidoa, the center of all conflicts
between Hussein Aidid's men and those of RRA last week.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people, mainly women and children, can be seen
now begging for food on the streets in Mogadishu where more
people are crowding in from the southern Somali regions,
especially Bay, middle and Lower Jubba which have been hit worst
by the recent natural disasters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
