<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Fraud Unearthed in Uganda's Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan police have unearthed a
racket of defrauders who diverted Kampala City Council (KCC)
checks worth 180 million Uganda Shillings (150,000 U.S. Dollars)
to their own accounts.
</P>
<P>
According to a Monitor's Monday report, the defrauders had been
diverting KCC's checks destined for banking at Gold Trust Bank.
</P>
<P>
Police said that one man they had arrested but refused to give
his name for sake of the ongoing investigations was part of a big
racket at City Hall and he connived to defraud the financially
unstable council.
</P>
<P>
The ring had diverted the money on various
occasions after erasing the word "council" from Kampala city
council checks, and have replaced it with the word "courier",
said the report.
</P>
<P>
The big fraud was only discovered when KCC officials went to
withdraw money on the accounts to pay salaries.
</P>
<P>
Simon Muhumza, KCC's Public Relations Officer, explained that
it's not KCC the institution itself but some individuals
collaborating with criminals from outside KCC that had been
involved in or abetting the theft.
</P>
<P>
He said that a number of banks are involved in the racket of
clearing diverted checks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
