<HEADLINE> England Beat Tunisia 2-0 in Group G Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MARSEILLE, June 15 (Xinhua) -- England opened their World Cup
campaign with a 2-0 victory over Tunisia in the Group G opener at
Marseille on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The victory was marred by clashes between England fans, Tunisia
supporters and French police on the beach of Marseille.
</P>
<P>
The organisers asked the Tunisian supporters remain on the stand
of the Stade Velodorme for at least 15 minutes after the match when
the England fans take the time to leave the stadium.
</P>
<P>
The match itself was also tense with three yellow cards issued.
England had a slow start and took nearly 30 minutes to assume
advantage.
</P>
<P>
Alan Shearer looked sharp, Teddy Sheringham had a powerful shot
at the goal only blocked by Tunisian goal-keeper Chokri El Ouaer.
</P>
<P>
Shearer finally broke the deadlock as he headed home a free-kick
from Graeme Le Saux at the 42nd minute.
</P>
<P>
England continued their domination in the second half but failed
to score again until the 89th minute. Paul Scholes picked up a
loose ball just out of the area and beat the Tunisian defence line
and the goal-keeper with a right-footer to put England 2-0 ahead.
</P>
<P>
Scholes showed he was in brilliant form and had several attempts at
the goal denied by the Tunisian goal-keeper in the first half.
</P>
<P>
Teenager striker Michael Owen replaced Sheringham in the second
half but failed to make his mark in his first World Cup match.
</P>
</TEXT>
