<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Releases Report on 1997 Employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government announced
here today that the urban registered unemployment rate for 1997
was 3.1 percent, 0.1 of a percentage point higher than in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, there were 5.768 million jobless
people in towns and cities who had been registered with their
local governments, according to a report released here today by
the Ministry of Labor and Social Security and the State Statistics
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
There were also 6.343 million workers laid off from
state-owned enterprises who had not found new jobs by the end
of 1997, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that at the end of 1997, China had a total
labor resource of 845.7 million people, among whom 696 million had
been provided with adequate work, including 146.684 million
workers and 26.69 million self-employed people in the urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Experts point out that China has an extremely large army of
surplus rural laborers, whose number exceeds 130 million even
according to conservative estimates.
</P>
<P>
Despite the massive layoffs in many loss-suffering state-owned
enterprises in recent years, the state sector remains the
predominant employer of China's urban residents.
</P>
<P>
Among China's 146.684 million urban workers, 107.659 million
worked in the state sector at the end of 1997, while another 28.17
million were employed by collective enterprises. Workers in the
non-public sector only totalled 10.855 million.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said that, compared with 1996, the number of
public sector employees in the cities decreased by more than 3.2
million in 1997, while the non-public sector hired nearly 1.5
million more people.
</P>
<P>
The year 1997 also witnessed the mushrooming of job placement
centers in various Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
The report said that there are currently more than 34,000
employment service institutions of various kinds across China,
which helped some 8.7 million people to find jobs and provided
vocational training for nearly three million people in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It added that the Re-employment Project carried out by
governments at all levels also helped more than 4.3 million
workers laid off from the state sector to find new employment
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The report also showed that by the end of 1997 the number of
retired workers nationwide totalled 33.5 million, an increase
of 1.39 million over 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
