<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Russia to Enhance Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Russia
Monday vowed to strengthen bilateral ties as their future as
custodians of the world's strategic mineral riches are
inextricably linked, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
A lull in relations between the two belonged to the past and
the two countries should do everything in their power to elevate
their relations to a new level, Sergei Yastrzhembski, special
envoy for Russian President Boris Yeltsin, said in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with South African Deputy Foreign Minister
Aziz Pahad, Yastrzhembski said that there had been a pause in the
relations between their two countries because the political
transition in Russia required undivided attention.
</P>
<P>
"Russia has now resumed speaking with a clear voice on
international issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pahad said that he hoped Yastrzhembski's visit will enable the
two countries to embark on decisive steps to extend bilateral
ties.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa and Russia possess the largest deposits of
strategic minerals in the world. Our futures are very linked.
What one does impacts on the other," Pahad said.
</P>
<P>
He said that a visit by Deputy President Thabo Mbeki to Russia
in September will give further impetus to the drive to strengthen
bilateral ties. Mbeki will be accompanied in the visit by Trade
and Industry Minister Alec Erwin and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
South Africa also has much to learn from Russia in the field
of technology, Pahad said, adding that Mbeki's visit will
hopefully result in economic, technical, cultural and other
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembski, who met Mbeki earlier in the day, said that
there were no differences in their discussion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
