<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stock Exchange Unveils Strategic Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong
Monday (SEHK) announced a three-year strategic plan, which calls
for major changes to make the Hong Kong stock market
well-positioned for intense competition in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
The plan, entitled "Positioning for a New Era," addresses two
concerns in the current stock market -- the low level of market
alignment and regulatory loopholes.
</P>
<P>
In this strategic plan for the years between 1998 and 2001, the
SEHK will develop a straight-through transaction process to create
better linkage between various institutions and systems in the
transaction chain and reduce cost, risk and delays.
</P>
<P>
The SEHK will also conduct a review of loopholes in the current
regulatory regime and make regulatory recommendations.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive of the Exchange Alex Tsui said here Monday that
the rapid improvement on these two fronts will enhance the
Exchange's appeal to international investors, who are deeply
concerned about the cost and efficiency of transaction and
regulatory standards.
</P>
<P>
"The environment for the Exchange has become much more
challenging," said Tsui, who noted that the Hang Seng index has
gone down 50 percent from the peak of more than 16,000 points in
August last year and the Hong Kong bourse now ranks 12th rather
than 6th in the world in terms of market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it was more urgent than ever for Hong Kong to
strengthen its competitiveness and to satisfy demanding customers.
The new strategic plan will help Hong Kong deal with keen
competition and capitalize on opportunities for business growth,
Tsui added.
</P>
<P>
The SEHK is aimed at boosting its market capitalization to 6
trillion HK dollars (769 billion U.S. dollars) by the year 2000 by
listing 250 China-related companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
