<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientist Invents New Fire-Extinguishing System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 15 (Xinhua) -- An automatic fire-extinguishing
system that does not need either electricity or manual labor has
been invented by a Chinese scientist, Piao Longkui.
</P>
<P>
The new system has been judged by a panel of experts from the
Ministry of Construction and the Ministry of Public Security as
capable of reducing over-reliance on fire engines and greatly
decreasing fire disasters.
</P>
<P>
The automatic fire detecting and fighting system is a
crystalization of 25 patented technologies owned by Piao, a
researcher at the China Academy of Launch Vehicle Technology. It
is produced by the Beijing Great Wall Sun Kwang Feed Water
Equipment Co., Ltd, a China-Republic of Korea joint venture.
</P>
<P>
The widespread use of electrical appliances and gas pipes in
modern life increases the potential for sporadic fires, and raises
an urgent demand for a fire-fighting system that reacts promptly
to fire disasters and quenches them at the earliest possible stage.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that China's current fire-extinguishing systems are
technically at the level common early in this century, while fire
hydrants and portable fire extinguishers are usually somewhat
complicated to operate for ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
They point out that fire engines which rush through heavy
traffic in cities usually arrive too late to save buildings which
are on fire.
</P>
<P>
A huge furniture shop in Southwestern Beijing caught fire on
May 6 and was burned to ashes despite the efforts of the crews of
more than 80 fire engines.
</P>
<P>
A report released today by the Ministry of Labor and Social
Security and the State Statistics Bureau says that fire poses as
great a threat to China as any other kind of disasters.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China saw over 140,000 fire disasters, excluding
those that took place in the forests and prairies, 3.8 times the
figure for the previous year. The fires caused direct economic
losses totalling 1.54 billion yuan, 49.5 percent more than in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa On Asian Economic Crisis In Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sydney, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Asia had not yet seen the worst of
the economic crisis and the next few quarters would become even
more painful for the region and its neighbors, said Tung Chee Hwa,
Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR), Monday in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Tung, in an address to an international business luncheon, said
that the Asian economic turmoil had caused Hong Kong to experience
not only a higher interest rate and a downturn in tourism, but an
overall negative growth in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
"The economy will be even more difficult in the next few
quarters," Tung told more than 300 audiences.
</P>
<P>
However, Tung remained confident about the prospects of Hong
Kong, saying when Hong Kong picks up the pieces, it would be much
happier, prosperous, healthier and fairer.
</P>
<P>
"We are going through a difficult period, but we will get
through it stronger and better than ever before," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong would continue with its massive plan of
investment in capital infrastructure and education, specifically
in schools, information technology and the environment for the
future.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Tung called on the Japanese government to boost
the yen, saying the currency's dramatic fall was reigning the
financial turmoil and damaging economies throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
"We are all in this together, what we can do is to pursue the
Japanese government to get on with it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The situation will get worse before it gets any better, that
is why I am here, to exchange views with the Australian
government."
</P>
<P>
Tung leaves for Melbourne Monday night and is due to deliver a
keynote address to the opening of the Australia Summit by Prime
Minister John Howard Tuesday.  Then, he will leave for New
Zealand on Wednesday morning to meet with Prime Minister Jenny
Shipley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
