<HEADLINE> Canadian Aircraft Not Joining Show of Force near Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Canadian aircraft will not take
part in the scheduled show of NATO air power near the troubled
Kosovo region of Yugoslavia, The Globe and Mail newspaper reported
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Scores of NATO warplanes will conduct low-level flights on
Monday over Albania and Macedonia in a quickly organized show of
force designed to demonstrate alliance resolve and force Serbian
leader Slobodan Milosevic to cease the "ethnic cleansing" in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Although Canadian Defense Minister Arthur Eggleton said "we
certainly want to participate" last week when NATO unveiled plans
for exercises, Canadian air force planners were "still looking at
all the options" Sunday, according to a Defense Department
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
NATO moved too quickly for Canada to get a "six-pack" of its
CF-18 warplanes ready and across the Atlantic on short
notice. However, if the aerial exercises over Albania and
Macedonia continue as expected, there may eventually be Canadian
involvement, according to the Canadian newspaper. 
