<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Follows Japanese Yen's Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar followed
the Japanese yen down a slippery dip against the U.S. dollar
Monday to close more than half a U.S. cent lower.
</P>
<P>
The weakness in the Japanese currency and a lower gold price
impacted heavily on the Australian dollar, driving it to a low of
58.50 U.S. cents on the day.
</P>
<P>
At the close in Sydney the Australian dollar was trading at
58.59 U.S. cents, from 59.17 U.S. cents previously, and gold ended
at 285.00 U.S. dollars, down 2.90 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar's recent slide has put financial markets
on alert for a possible rise in official interest rates in Sydney
by the Reserve Bank of Australia, the nation's central bank.
</P>
<P>
Economists have suggested that a rate lift by the central bank
as a counter attack against the recent wave of selling of the
currency is unlikely, but market participants remain alert for
such a move.
</P>
<P>
With little in the way of economic data to look forward to this
week, the only release is the Australian Bureau of Statistics Wage
Cost Index on Thursday, and attention has turned to the fallout of
the One Nation Party's at least 10-seat win in the Queensland
state election over the past weekend.
</P>
<P>
Most economists contend that One Nation Party will have a
negative effect on financial markets as it implies increased
pressure on the ruling Liberal/National coalition to peg back its
tax reform, telecommunications giant Telstra' privatization and
business competition agenda.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was buying 85.41 Japanese yen, from 85.16
yen previously, and 1.0614 German marks, from 1.0690 marks.
</P>
</TEXT>
