<HEADLINE> Indonesian MP Urges U.S. to Act For Releasing IMF Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- An Indonesian legislator Monday
urged the United States to quickly respond to two letters sent by
Indonesian legislators last week on the immediate release of
International Monetary Fund's (IMF) loans to the country.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that there would be immediate answers from President
(Bill) Clinton and the U.S. Congress because U.S. Ambassador to
Indonesia J. Stapleton Roy has promised to convey our letters to
them," Abu Hasan Sazili said.
</P>
<P>
Six legislators delivered the two letters to Roy Saturday, with
one addressed to Clinton and the other to the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
The two letters were signed by 89 of the 500 members of the
House of Representatives (DPR).
</P>
<P>
Sazili said that in the two letters, the legislators conveyed
their appreciation for U.S. aid given to non-government
organizations (NGOs) in efforts to strengthen human rights, the
environment and democratization in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
He said they, however, underscored control over the aid so that
it would not be exploited for the interests of certain groups and
expressed the hope that the U.S. would not meddle in Indonesia's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The immediate disbursement of IMF funds could strengthen the
IMF's credibility and avoid the impression that the financial
institution is only "kidding" Indonesia, he said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF promised last October to provide 10 billion U.S.
dollars of a 43-billion-U.S.-dollar package which the agency
brokered to bail out Indonesia's ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia received the first tranche of 3 billion dollars from
the IMF in November last year, but the second disbursement of 3
billion U.S. dollars scheduled for June was delayed due to riots
in Jakarta in May and the later political crisis in the country
which forced former president Soeharto to step down.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said it will disburse the aid early next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
