<HEADLINE> Peace March Needs New Impetus: Labor Leader Barak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Israeli opposition Labor
Party leader Ehud Barak said Monday that it was necessary to give
a new push to the Middle East peace process for the benefit of
Israelis and Palestinians alike.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak,
Barak said he had come out of his talks with an impression that
there was concern because of the slow pace in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
His meeting with Mubarak, he said, took place one day after
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat talked with Mubarak about their
anxiety over the stagnant peace process and their wish to give it
new momentum.
</P>
<P>
"This was also the wish of the Israeli Labor Party and the
majority of Israeli public opinion," Barak added.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the latest American initiative to
reactivate the Mideast peace drive, Barak said he was of the view
that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu should go to
Washington at once, reach an agreement on a second stage
redeployment and move forward towards final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"The Labor Party supports the implementation of the second
stage redeployment of Israeli troops in the West Bank," he said,
adding the support has been conveyed to Israeli public.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli opposition leader did not wish to discuss figures
and percentages, but said the ideas contained in the American
offer "are good."
</P>
<P>
Barak said he told Mubarak about the feeling of the majority of
Israeli people and their wish to see the peace process continue so
that peace and security may prevail among the Israelis and
Palestinians and in the entire area.
</P>
<P>
He stressed his party believes that peace is the right course
to realize Israeli security and that negotiations with the
Palestinians could lead to an agreement on final status.
</P>
<P>
"It was necessary to continue direct negotiations on the final
status to avoid other alternatives which could lead to a
deterioration in the entire peace process," he added.
</P>
<P>
Barak disliked Netanyahu's idea to hold a referendum on further
redeployment in order to beat right-wing opposition within his
Likud-led coalition, saying it would be a waste of time and money.
</P>
<P>
"It would cost a lot of money and would take several
months. And we know the result in advance. We know that 75 percent
of Israelis want an understanding on carrying out a second stage
redeployment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Barak's visit to Cairo came on the heels of that of Israeli
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai early this month, who discussed
with Mubarak means of reviving the peace process on the
Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Labor Party lawmaker and assistant to
late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, Youssi Belein, arrived
here Sunday night for a hours-long visit during which he held
talks with Mubarak's political advisor Osama el-Baz on the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli talks came to a halt in March 1997 when
Israel started construction of a new Jewish settlement in Arab
East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
