<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan MPs Demand Govt to Explain Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Parliamentarians will
this week demand an explanation from the government on how the
rebels could burn over 80 students to death in a recent massacre
without receiving any resistance from the military.
</P>
<P>
This will be the latest expression of anxiety over security as
the Ugandan government comes under mounting pressure to open
peace talks with the rebels, the weekly East African newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some members of parliament added their voices to calls by
human rights groups, opposition politicians, and religious
leaders for halting the killings in the insurgency-hit areas of
western and northern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
On June 8, a group of some 200 rebels of the Allied Democratic
Forces (ADF) mounted a pre-dawn attack on the Kichwamba Technical
Institute in Kabarole District in west Uganda, burning more than 80
students to death and abducting many others.
</P>
<P>
While the cruelty of the rebels has been a target of fierce
criticism from all walks of life in Uganda, the no-resistance
from the Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) is more
ruthlessly blamed.
</P>
<P>
Novert Mao, an outspoken MP for Gulu Municipality which is
also frequently affected by insurgency, said, "The government
has to explain to parliament how such a thing happened."
</P>
<P>
"We shall summon these people to cone and explain how the
rebels attacked the students without any resistance from UPDF,"
Mao said.
</P>
<P>
The house will seek to know whether the funds allocated for
defense are justified if the army cannot defend the population,
he added.
</P>
<P>
In the 1998/99 budget unveiled last week, the defense spending
increased by 26 percent to 143 billion Uganda Shillings (119
million U.S. Dollars), accounting for 15 percent of the total
estimated revenue of 991.8 billion Shillings (826 million U.S.
Dollars), the biggest allocation of resources.
</P>
<P>
"What this latest attack has shown is that all the money we
are voting for defense is not justified. The army is not
accountable," he said. "The army's most vital problem is not
money but it's management. Those concerned will have to
explain."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
