<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1997 Industrial Accident Toll Drops to 17,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 15 (Xinhua) -- In 1997 China saw fewer accidents
take place in its industrial enterprises, and railway and water
transportation, but many more cases of fire and traffic accidents,
according to a report released by the Ministry of Labor and Social
Security and the State Statistics Bureau here today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in 1997 a total of 18,268 industrial
accidents occurred in enterprises nationwide, killing 17,558
people.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, the figures are respectively 12.5 and 9.8
percent lower compared with those in the previous year. The number
of major accidents also dropped 15.6 percent, to 696.
</P>
<P>
As usual, most of China's industrial accidents in 1997 occurred
in the mining industry, which suffered 7,266 accidents which
killed 11,265 miners. But even these two figures are 14.9 and 7.7
percent lower, respectively, than in 1996, said the report.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,600 accidents occurred last year in the country's
railway sector, three percent fewer than in 1996, said the report.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, fire and traffic accidents were the
greatest headache for China in 1997.
</P>
<P>
More than 140,000 cases of fire, not including forest and
prairie fires, were reported nationwide last year, 3.8 times as
many as in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The fire killed 2,722 people, injured 4,930 and caused direct
economic losses worth 1.54 billion yuan (nearly 200 million US
dollars). The figures represent 22.3, 43.8 and 49.5 percent up,
respectively, over the previous year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
China's civil aviation sector last year suffered four flight
accidents, which killed a total of 42 people, the report added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Links Euro Entry with National Interest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
on Monday restated that Britain's entry into the European single
currency should be based on the national economic interest.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with BBC radio, Blair said his government was
positive towards the concept of euro but would only join the
single currency if the British people wished to do so.
</P>
<P>
The first-round launch of the euro, agreed by 11 member states
from the 15-state European Union, will start early next year
without Britain.
</P>
<P>
The British government has ruled out joining the European
Monetary Union in the current term of parliament which ends in
2002.
</P>
<P>
"We are positive towards the overall concept of a single
currency. We are making preparations to allow Britain to join
should it wish to do so," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
However, Blair said the decision must be taken "on economic
grounds on the basis of what is in Britain's national economic
interest -- are the benefits of it clear and unambiguous".
</P>
<P>
"The reason for the delay is that we simply can't judge that at
this time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair's comments followed a statement on Sunday by Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook, which was interpreted by some commentators
as favoring British entry into the euro.
</P>
<P>
Sweden and Denmark are also staying out of the single currency,
while Greece failed to meet the criteria for entry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
