<HEADLINE> South Korea's Share Prices Down Below 300 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Seoul stocks tumbled below the
300-point level Monday, the lowest in 11 years, due to a further
weakening of the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The composite index plunged 4.82 percent or 14.6 points to
close at 288.21, with 735 listings falling and 97 rising while 54
remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Of the losers, 198 dropped to their daily limit lows and a mere
20 issues rose to their daily permissible highs.
</P>
<P>
The weakening Japanese yen also affected South Korea's currency
markets, with the won was trading at 1,432 against the
U.S. dollar, compared with 1,403 won last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The yen dropped to 145 against the greenback on Tokyo's foreign
exchange market Monday, the lowest rate in seven years and eight
months.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here attributed the tumble in the stock and foreign
exchange markets to the fears of a further fall in the Japanese
yen and continued selling of stocks by foreign and domestic
investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
