<HEADLINE> Egypt-U.S. Strategic Dialog Starts Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
will travel to Washington next month to open the Egyptian-American
strategic dialog designed to speed up bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Ambassador to the United States Ahmed Maher presented a
report Sunday to President Hosni Mubarak on Egyptian-American ties
in anticipation of the strategic talks, the Middle East News
Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The aim of this dialog is to create a fast communication
channel between the U.S. State Department and Egyptian Foreign
Ministry, Maher said after his meeting with Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
"It will enable each side to better understand the demands of
the other end to overcome any type of misunderstandings that might
arise and coordinate stances when required," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian ambassador said he also met with Moussa to examine
the agenda of the dialog, which will be dominated by the Middle
East peace process and the obstacles placed by Israel to the
implementation of a U.S. peace proposal.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian delegation made up of Minister of Economy Youssef
Boutros Ghali and Minister of State for Planning Zafer el-Bishri
will be in Washington next week to discuss issues related to the
Egyptian-U.S. partnership and follow up the results of U.S. Vice
President Al Gore's last visit to Egypt on May 3.
</P>
<P>
The Mubarak-Gore meeting focused on ways to improve bilateral
economic relations, encourage American investments in Egypt and
reactivate the four sub-committees of the Egyptian-American
Presidential Council which has been idle since its creation three
years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
