<HEADLINE> NATO Starts Air Exercise In Albania, Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- NATO warplanes began air exercises
over Albania and Macedonia Monday morning, aimed to step up
pressure on the Yugoslavian government to end the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
A total of 80 aircraft from 13 of the 16 countries in the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization have been involved in the air
maneuvers, codenamed Determined Falcon.
</P>
<P>
Around 40 NATO warplanes have flown over Tirana, the capital
of Albania, as part of the exercise in Albania and Macedonia which
border the Yugoslav province of Kosovo. On the ground, the sound
of aircraft engines was deafening.
</P>
<P>
The operation, the largest air exercise held by NATO in the
Balkan Peninsula, includes fighters, reconnaissance planes,
airborne early warning systems, air refuelling tankers and
helicopters, operating from the Aviano airbase in northern Italy
and other airbases in southern Europe.
</P>
<P>
The exercise came as fighting continued in Kosovo over the
weekend between Serbian police and ethnic Albanians, who make up
90 percent of Kosovo population.
</P>
<P>
NATO is piling pressure on Yugoslavian President Slobodan
Milosevic to stop the "crackdown" on ethnic Albanians and prevent
the conflict from spreading through the southern Balkans.
</P>
<P>
"On Kosovo, let me be quite clear that NATO will not stand idly
by," warned NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana in a speech in
Warsaw on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We will not allow a repeat of the situation of 1991 in
Bosnia."
</P>
<P>
More than 300 people have died and some 65,000 people become
refugees since the Serb-led government of the Yugoslav
federation began "a military crackdown" on the ethnic Albanian
independence movement in Kosovo early this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
