<HEADLINE> Nigerian Parties Divided on Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's five political parties
are now divided on transition to civil rule program following the
sudden death of their consensus presidential candidate, late head
of state, General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said Monday that differences emerged at
the meeting between the parties and the new leader General
Abdulsalam Abubakar which lasted from Saturday evening until
early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Four of the parties, namely, the Democratic Party of Nigeria
(DPN), the National Centre Party of Nigeria (NCPN), the Congress
for National Consensus (CNC) and the Grassroots Democratic
Movement (GDM) demanded the cancellation of the state and
national assembly elections held on December 6, 1997 and April 25
this year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The four parties, which lost miserably to the United Nigeria
Congress Party (UNCP) in the said elections, accused some
government ministers of interferring in the elections in favor of
the UNCP.
</P>
<P>
Their suggestion was, of course, resisted by the UNCP.
</P>
<P>
The five parties, however, do reached preliminary consensus on
the point that the August 1 presidential election date should
maintain, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
They also objected the idea of dissolving them, as have been
canvanssed by the some sectors of the society, on the ground that
all the five parties are "government parties".
</P>
<P>
According to reports, the new Nigerian Head of State, General
Abubakar has urged the parties to reach a general consensus on
key issues concerning the transition program.
</P>
<P>
The parties were told to come with a common position at their
next meeting with Abubakar Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting at the weekend is part of the consultations held
by Abubakar as to how to continue with the transition program
introduced by Abacha three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar has promised to carry on with the transiton program,
even though he is left with less than two months to the
presidential election now deprived of its sole candidate.
</P>
<P>
The meeting were also attended the National Electoral
Commission of Nigeria, the Transition Implementation Committee,
as well as service chiefs and the Inspector-General of Police,
reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
