<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower on Further Asian Weakness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
closed softer Monday on further Asian weakness despite the
spectacular and successful float of the AMP LTD, Australia's
financial services giant.
</P>
<P>
AMP's listing at the Australian Stock Exchange Monday afternoon
at 35.99 Australian dollars, up off a base price of 16 Australian
dollars, dominated market interest.
</P>
<P>
The ordinary shares of the company closed at 23.00 Australian
dollars, considerably higher than the 20 Australian dollars
predicted by many experts.
</P>
<P>
Trading in AMP so dominated the market that turnover in it
alone was higher than the value of trade in all other stocks
combined.
</P>
<P>
Overall, 277.47 million shares changed hands worth 987.24
million U.S. dollars but more than half of that was AMP-related as
its 35 million shares were worth 504.6 million U.S. dollars alone.
</P>
<P>
Falling shares outnumbered rising shares by 599 to 433.
</P>
<P>
However, as AMP is excluded from the all ordinaries index until
August 1, the float had no direct affect on an otherwise
lackluster all ordinaries index but its success limited broader
falls, according to brokers.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed down 4.2 points at 2567.5, the
all industrials gained 7.1 to 4481.7 while all resources softened
15.6 to 1027.0.
</P>
<P>
News Corp's ordinary shares closed 64.1 cents firmer at 11.201
Australian dollars and its preferred shares climbed 39.1 cents to
9.491 Australian dollars thanks mainly to its renewed strength in
the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks also ended the day higher but most other leading
shares gave up ground with the heaviest losses in the resource and
building materials sectors.
</P>
<P>
Bank shares ended 10.5 points higher overall at 5541.7 points
thanks mainly to a 34.7-cent rise in National Australia Bank
shares to 21.40 Australian dollars and the Commonwealth Bank of
Australia's 5.8-cent rise to 17.508 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other majors were all weaker with Westpac bank 17 cents lower
at 9.40 Australian dollars and ANZ bank down 12 cents to 10.50
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP closed 11 cents lower at 13.12 Australian
dollars, Rio Tinto slipped 20.9 cents to 19.05 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index also tumbled 2.4 percent (26.2 points) to 1063.6
while the gold bullion price was down 2.9 U.S. dollars to 285.00
U.S. dollars late in Sydney trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
