<HEADLINE> Israeli "Kitchen Cabinet" Fails to Decide on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu held his "Kitchen Cabinet" meeting here on Monday to
discuss Israeli troop redeployment in the West Bank, but no
decision was made, a statement issued by the Prime Minister's
Office said.
</P>
<P>
The "Kitchen Cabinet" members National Infrastructure Minister
Ariel Sharon, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Industry and
Trade Minister Natan Sharansky attended the meeting, according to
the statement.
</P>
<P>
"They discussed the scope of the further Israeli troop
redeployment in the West Bank, but could not reach a conclusion on
the depth of the redeployment and so they decided to further
discuss this mater during the next few days," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The United States earlier this month gave Israel about 10 days
to make its decision on whether to accept the U.S. initiative for
the peace process, threatening to reconsider its policy toward the
process and announce its initiative as asked by the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
But as the so-called deadline comes nearer, the United States
has done nothing in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The English-language newspaper "the Jerusalem Post" reported on
Monday that Netanyahu is holding off his proposal for the next
Israeli troop redeployment in the West Bank until the middle of
July, to allow time for the PNA to meet his preconditions.
</P>
<P>
He reportedly wanted to make sure the U.S. administration will
be able to arrange a White House signing ceremony for the pullback
agreement with PNA President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a senior government source as saying that
Israel will make crucial decision on redeployment in the coming
three or four weeks while the Knesset (Parliament) is still in
summer session, which is to last till the first week of August.
</P>
<P>
The paper also said that Netanyahu is taking the advantage of
some international events for his delay in making decision on the
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Such events include U.S. President Bill Clinton's visit to
China, the ongoing crisis in Kosovo and the aftermath of the
Indian and Pakistani nuclear tests as well as the economic
instability in southeast Asia, which have been taking
precedence of the U.S. State Department's traditional concern
about the Middle East, according to the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
