<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Trade Deficit Up 4.2 percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' trade deficit rose by 50.8
million Cyprus pounds (101.6 million U.S. dollars) in 1997, up 4.2
percent than that in 1996, according to a report available here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report issued by the Department of Statistics and Research
said the 1997 trade deficit stood at 1,259.3 million pounds (2,518.6
million dollars) due to a 2.3 percent rise in import and 1.4
percent drop in export.
</P>
<P>
The imports in 1997 hit 1,899.3 million pounds (3,798.6 million
dollars), 41.8 million pounds (83.6 million dollars) up from 1996,
while the export fell to 640 million pounds (1,280 million dollars)
from 649 million pounds (1,398 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The report said the European Union (EU) remained the chief
exporter to Cyprus last year, but its market share fell by one
percentage point to 56.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The imports from the United States stood at 360 million pounds
(720 million dollars), while imports from Arab countries slid by a
drastical 48.6 percent to 36.2 million pounds (72.4 million
dollars) last year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' exports to Arab countries soared by 17.7 percent to
131.2 million pounds (262.4 million dollars) last year, following
the exports to European countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
