<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists Recommend Easier Loans for Small Firms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's commercial banks were asked last month to set up
special departments lending to medium- and small-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Lin noted that it is better for local financial organizations,
such as the urban and rural credit cooperatives, to engage in
such work, instead of the national commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
"They are relatively familiar with the local situation, which
can greatly reduce their costs of investigation, evaluation and
supervision of local enterprises applying for loans." said Lin.
</P>
<P>
China's four-largest state-run commercial banks -- the
Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, the Agricultural Bank
of China, the China Construction Bank and the Bank of China --
occupy the dominant position in the country's financial system.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Qiu said, "Large banks have their own distinct
advantages, and so do the smaller ones. The latter are better for
their relatively flexible operations."
</P>
<P>
He suggested that China encourage the development of
small-sized financial firms in line with the local economic
situations, in a bid to support medium- and-small-sized
enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
