<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marseille to Ban Sale of Alcohol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Marseille shops will be banned from
selling alcohol from 16:40 Monday, and bars will be closed by
23:00 instead of 04:00, said an official from
Provence-Alpes-Cote-d'Azur Jean-Paul Proust.
</P>
<P>
These measures were taken after violent clashes between drunken
English football hooligans and Tunisian fans erupted in the city
from Sunday night to Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
The English football team is now playing Tunisia at the
Velodrome Stadium of Marseille, a city with a great North African
community.
</P>
<P>
French police accused English fans of "group drunkenness" and
provoking fights with Tunisians, during which 37 were injured.
</P>
<P>
Beer bottles were used by the fans of both sides during the
fight and were thrown at police who tried to stop them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some highly frequented bars along the breathtaking
river side of old port Marseille, including the famous Bar de la
Marine which was depicted by the great French writer Marcel
Pagnol, were closed Monday morning out of precaution.
</P>
<P>
But no accident took place Monday morning between the English
fans and Tunisian fans, who strolled under sunlight in the old
port.
</P>
<P>
Police have been checking arriving English fans at the
Saint-Charles railway station of Marseille, searching their packs
and giving safe guide when they go out of the station.
</P>
<P>
The state railway company SNCF is offering special rail lines
for the trains departing from Calais and Paris carrying English
fans, in order to let them ride in the best conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
