<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fluoridated Water Efficient to Prevent Tooth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Fluoridated water is the
"most efficient" way to prevent tooth decay, a senior official of
the South African Health Department said at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Nine out of 10 people in South Africa experienced tooth decay
by the time they reached adulthood.
</P>
<P>
"Tooth decay is the most common disease known to
humankind...yet it is a preventable disease," the Business
Day Monday quoted Johan Smit, Director of Oral health in the
Health Department, as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Fluoridated water would render tooth decay more of a "thing of
the past, and save the government millions, Smit said.
</P>
<P>
Smit said it had been scientifically proven that tooth decay
could be reduced by up to 60 percent with fluoridated water.
</P>
<P>
It would cost only about one Rand (One U.S. Dollar equals 5.30
Rand) per person annually, which was 18 times cheaper than
toothpaste and 61 times cheaper than filling a tooth, he said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the South African government's plan to
make use of fluoridated water has not been free of controversy.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Pan-Africanist Congress has criticized the
ruling African National Congress for not instead spending the
money on campaigns to reduce the consumption of sweets by
children and on making school meals healthier for their teeth.
</P>
<P>
Other detractors have citied studies showing fluoride posed a
cancer risk, although several international medical bodies
including the World Health Organization insist that it is safe at
low levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
