<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indo-U.S. Relations In For Difficult Patch: U.S. Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to India Richard
F. Celeste said Monday that the bilateral ties between India and
the United States after India's nuclear tests are in for a
difficult patch, though the door is open for a high-level
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Press Trust of India (PTI) here,
Celeste said: "If we are realistic, I believe, we are in for a
difficult patch. There is a great deal of talk about sanctions and
also speculations here. The sanctions would be real and serious
and would have an impact on India and Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
He said that these sanctions were the first to be imposed under
the Glen Amendment of the United States and Washington had no road
map to guide it. "But perhaps, the most difficult aspect of these
sanctions is that they can be lifted only by an act of Congress,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Apart from their direct impact, the sanctions would also have
indirect fallout which could erode the confidence of investors
from the United States and other countries in India, he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether India's nuclear tests had put President Bill
Clinton's planned visit to India this November under a cloud,
Celeste said: "Well, just now it is under review."
</P>
<P>
"President Clinton has certainly expressed his desire to come
to India at an appropriate time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was giving a great deal of personal time and efforts to
securing successful negotiations on the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty (CTBT) which is now awaiting ratification in the U.S. There
was a great deal of "disappointment and concern" in Washington
about the tests which had several dimensions on the global efforts
to reduce and eliminate nuclear weapons and increased tension,
danger and insecurity in South Asia, the U.S. Ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
"These are the two over-riding concerns driving the policy of
not only the U.S. government but many other governments who share
these concerns," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked why the United States and key countries were
focusing on Kashmir and linking it with the Indian nuclear tests,
he said that this was due to the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party
(BJP) talking about India exercising the nuclear option in its
manifesto which also referred to Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"After the nuclear tests by India, Home Minister L. K. Advani
seemed to link the country's nuclear weapons capability with the
issue of Kashmir, which was followed by Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee traveling to the test site in the company of Jammu and
Kashmir Chief Minister Farooq Abdullah," Celeste said.
</P>
<P>
These factors "powerfully link" Kashmir with the nuclear tests
and it should come as no surprise to India that leaders in the
United States and elsewhere be very concerned about Kashmir, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Washington's policy on Kashmir was very clear. It should be
resolved through direct and constructive talks between India and
Pakistan, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We believe sooner the talks get underway, it will be better
for both the countries and for the stability in the
sub-continent," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0108 </DOCNO>
