<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's New Budget Hurts Manufactures: Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's budget for the 1998/99
fiscal year, which favors importers and consumers, will
eventually hurt manufacturers in the country, a member of
parliament has said.
</P>
<P>
Manzi Tumubweine, Chairman of the Parliamentary Committee on
Finance and Planning, was quoted by Monday's East African Weekly
as saying that the reduction of taxes on imports, though easy on
consumers and importers, would ultimately hurt manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
"Unless other new measures are introduced, imports will be
cheaper than locally produced goods. One will need to be
patriotic to import raw materials," he said.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts here said that the import-oriented budget is
unlikely to promote poverty alleviation programs as it will take
money out of the economy.
</P>
<P>
"You cannot talk of poverty alleviation when you are
encouraging importation," a member of the Uganda Manufacturers
Association commented.
</P>
<P>
Even since the new budget was presented to parliament last
Thursday, manufacturers have been complaining about changes made
in the taxation system to accommodate COMESA. The taxes were
changed from a four-rate duty system of 0 percent, 5 percent, 10
percent and 20 percent to a three-rate regime of 0 percent, 7
percent and 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tumubweine said that the reduction in taxers will discourage
local manufacturing while promoting importation. Taxes on raw
material imports are now almost at par with finished goods.
</P>
<P>
Concern by the manufacturers and analysts also centered on the
government's failure to set up an investment fund for local
investors.
</P>
<P>
They also complain about the government's failure to come up
with measures to control smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Over the last two fiscal years, the government has lost up to
90 billion Uganda Shillings (7.5 million U.S. Dollars) of
projected revenue collection, partly due to rampant smuggling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
