<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lake Victoria Heavily Polluted by Wastes: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Mining activities have
heavily polluted Lake Victoria, the world's second largest
freshwater lake, said a Tanzanian environment official.
</P>
<P>
In some small mines on the shores of the lake, mercury is
contaminating ground and surface water, Monday's Daily News
quoted Angelina Madete, who works at the Environment Division in
the Vice-President's Office, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a workshop on prospects for sustainable management
of Lake Victoria over the weekend in Mwanza, Madete said that
environmentally-accepted method for panning requires the use of
special devices to separate mercury from pure gold instead of
open burning and washing.
</P>
<P>
The Mwanza municipality alone has 43 factories which discharge
untreated waste into the lake, said Madete.
</P>
<P>
However, the government lacks in legislations and pollution
control facilities to deal with this problem, she said.
</P>
<P>
Another major source of pollution in the lake is pit latrines
and septic tanks which are commonly used by local residents, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, heavy pollution has caused the rampant growth
of water hyacinth in the lake, hampering the free movement of
vessels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
