<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Plunge to Three-year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks plunged 5.72
percent to more than three-year low Monday, due to rising local
interbank rates and increasing pressure from the weakening
Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng index dropped 452.94 points to close at
7,462.50 points Monday. It was the key benchmark's lowest since
January 16, 1995 when it recorded 7.504.24 points.
</P>
<P>
The market's turnover registered at 6,239 million HK dollars
(800 million U.S. dollars), 252 million HK dollars (32 million
U.S. dollars) more than that of last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index lost 129 points, or 1.63 percent, to
open at 7,786 Monday morning. It lost 369.57 points, or 4.67
percent, to close at 7,545.87 at midday.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong shares rebounded 29.37 points, or 0.37 percent, to
close at 7,915 last Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
