<HEADLINE> HK Makes Sustained Efforts to Tackle Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The seasonally adjusted
unemployment rate for the period February to April 1998 in Hong
Kong was 3.9 percent, Secretary for Education and Manpower Joseph
W. P. Wong said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Wong told a press briefing that the underemployment rate for
the same period was 2.2 percent. He added that the provisional
seasonally adjusted unemployment rate for March to May was 4.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Acting government economist Elley Mao explained that the
increase in unemployment rate occurred mainly in retail,
restaurants and transport sectors.
</P>
<P>
By comparison, the unemployment situation in other major
sectors was "broadly stable," she added.
</P>
<P>
Wong noted that the government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region was "very concerned about the employment
situation" and has announced a package of measures recently to
tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
When the task force led by Financial Secretary Donald Tsang
meets again in July 9 to review the employment situation, Wong
said, further measures will be announced.
</P>
<P>
Admitting the high unemployment rate will last for some time,
Wong said employment prospects in foreseeable future are
"positive" since Hong Kong's economic fundamentals remain sound
and strong.
</P>
<P>
While reaffirming the government's commitment to creating more
job opportunities, he called for sustained, collective and
concerted efforts of the whole community to tackle the employment
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
