<HEADLINE> Roundup: Groups Emerge to Help Macao Transitional Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Grassroots communities and societies
in Macao have established more than 20 specialized groups to
collect opinions on Macao's transition and the preparation for the
future Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
Over the month since the establishment of the Macao SAR
Preparatory Committee in Beijing on May 5, various groups like
"working committee for the upcoming handover," "group embracing
Macao's return," "group following SAR preparatory committee's
affairs" have come into being in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Founders of these groups include such grassroots bodies as the
Macao Association of Neighborhood Communities, Macao Federation of
Trade Unions, Macao Women's Federation and the Macao Ambulant
Sellers Community.
</P>
<P>
Business and specialized groups as the Youth Committee of the
Macao Chamber of Commerce, the Association of Returned Overseas
Chinese in Macao, the Chinese Education Association, Factory
Owners Society, and the Macao Society of Economics Study have also
established similar groups.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of these groups, according to some founders, are
to collect opinions from members and make studies on certain
transitional affairs, and hand over proposals on those issues to
the Preparatory Committee.
</P>
<P>
"To create a better Macao SAR tomorrow, we need the
participation and creative ideas from all Macao residents," said
Pun Hun Veng, member of the Preparatory Committee, who heads the
working committee for the handover under the Macao Association of
Trade Unions.
</P>
<P>
"Our group is to listen to opinions from all our members on the
issues the Preparatory Committee is to address, and submit our
suggestions on those issues," Pun added.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said that his group will also make more efforts
to spread the knowledge of the Macao Basic Law among members and
other citizens in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The emergence of these groups has been applauded by local
media, which said it shows the enthusiasm of Macao residents for
the upcoming return to the motherland in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"These groups will help canvas opinions from all walks of life
in Macao," said a commentary in the newspaper Va Kio. "It also
shows the support and care for the work of the Preparatory
Committee and their great attention to the formation of the future
Macao SAR." 
</P>
</TEXT>
