<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Constitutional Council Holds First Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The first meeting of Cambodia's
Constitutional Council, crucial to the forthcoming elections, was
held on Monday, with former Supreme Court President Chan Sok
chosen as its president.
</P>
<P>
Seven of the Constitutional Council's nine appointees attended
the meeting, which lasted nearly four hours, and Chan Sok won five
votes in a secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
Chan Sok, 69, said that the Constitutional Council could then
carry out its duty. The council, sworn in on June 2, is the final
arbiter on the constitutionality of laws.
</P>
<P>
Two attempts to hold such a meeting failed due to a boycott by
two senior members, Chau Sen Cocsal Chhum and Son Sann, who were
appointed by King Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
The two were still absent at Monday's meeting, but it reached a
required quorum of seven.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was called and chaired by the third eldest royal
appointee, Pung Peng Cheng, who declared on Saturday that he would
resign after the meeting due to his old age.
</P>
<P>
Opposition critics, however, complained that most members of
the council were biased towards the Cambodian People's Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
