<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Eases in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The downward trend in inflation
that started in March continued into May in Kenya, said the June
edition of Monthly Economic Review by the Central Bank of Kenya
(CBK) available Monday.
</P>
<P>
The decline is a result of improved supplies of basic foods
during the second quarter of 1998, the sustained slowdown in the
expansion of money supply, and the general stability in the
shilling exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The underlying three-month annualized inflation fell to 3.3
percent in May from 34.2 percent in March and 25.9 percent in
April.
</P>
<P>
The underlying month-on-month inflation declined to 10.8
percent in May from 12.3 percent in April while underlying
average annual inflation increased to 7.7 percent in May from 7.4
percent in April.
</P>
<P>
The response of the average index is slow because of the price
increases early this year.
</P>
<P>
Overall inflation also continued to decline, with the
three-month annualized inflation falling to 0.6 percent in May
from 34.7 percent in March and 13.1 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
The overall month-on-month and average annual inflation also
declined to 4.6 and 8.8 percent in May from 7.0 and 9.9 percent
in April respectively.
</P>
<P>
The month-on-month inflation for the lower income group fell
for the third consecutive month to 2.7 percent in May compared
with 7.1 percent in March and 5.9 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
The month-on-month inflation for the middle and upper income
groups however rose to 11.0 percent and 11.4 percent from 10.5
percent and 10.6 percent respectively in April.
</P>
<P>
The down in the underlying inflation was explained by the
sustained slow expansion of broad money supply consistent with
the slowdown in aggregate demand, said the CBK review.
</P>
<P>
The continued stability in the Shilling exchange rate also
helped to dampen the inflationary pressures implicit in import
pricing.
</P>
<P>
To confine the month-on-month inflation to the target range of
less than five percent by June, 1999, the annual expansion in
broad money supply should be maintained at below 10.0 percent,
said the bank.
</P>
<P>
The CBK also predicted that inflation is to continue declining
in the months ahead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Near to Being Free of U.N. Sanctions: Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Chief U.N. arms inspector Richard
Butler said here on Monday that Iraq is near to being free of
trade embargo if it continues fulfilling its promises of
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"The light at the end of the tunnel is today more visible than
it has been for a very long time, and we all welcome that," Butler
told a press conference before ending his five-day visit to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I am very positive about this, this is good news, provided
Iraq ... gives us access to the materials and documents" about the
weapons program, then "we will verify these materials quickly and
honestly," he added.
</P>
<P>
Butler is the chairman of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM)
charged with overseeing the elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Only when the UNSCOM verifies that Iraq has destroyed the
banned weapons, will the U.N. Security Council lift the crippling
economic sanctions imposed on Iraq in 1990 after its invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Butler said the UNSCOM and Iraq have reached an agreement on the
program of work for the next two months. But he did not disclose
the details.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM and Iraq reached an agreement Sunday night on the
program of work, a timetable for the completion of work, on
outstanding disarmament issues for the next two months, Butler
said.
</P>
<P>
Butler arrived here last Thursday for talks with Iraqi
government officials.
</P>
<P>
He held "long and detailed" discussions with Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz on arms inspections "on a technical level and
on a policy level" in the past days, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
