<HEADLINE> Economists Recommend Easier Loans for Smaller Firms (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Some of China's leading economists
have suggested that if the country is to achieve eight-percent
economic growth this year it should encourage non-governmental
investment and make it easier for medium- and small-sized
enterprises to obtain bank loans.
</P>
<P>
"Spurring non-governmental investment is quite important now,"
said Prof. Lin Yifu of Beijing University's China Economic
Research Center. "Most governmental investment is for
infrastructure construction, while that from non-government sources
goes mainly into the production sectors."
</P>
<P>
The economist noted that medium- and small-sized enterprises,
including joint ventures, and township and private firms, which
need less capital but can provide more working opportunities, have
so far been the major force speeding up China's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Qiu Zhaoxiang of the China Financial Institute agreed on
the vital role played by medium- and small-sized firms for China's
economic growth at a symposium on regional economic development
here.
</P>
