<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Govt to Unveil New Anti-AIDS Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's
special anti-AIDS team under Deputy President Thabo Mbeki has
developed an 80-million-Rand (15-million-U.S.-Dollar) plan, due
to be discussed at a national conference in August.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the seriousness of the HIV/AIDS epidemic,
the government will take a leadership role in mobilizing all sectors
in a comprehensive campaign to ensure a reduction in the spread
of HIV infection," the daily Citizen Monday quoted an official
summary of the plan as saying.
</P>
<P>
The plan goes into details of what different sectors of
the society should do as part of the mass campaign.
</P>
<P>
For example, the presidency "should incorporate AIDS-relevant
messages in all public speeches."  The South African
Broadcasting Corporation, as public broadcaster, "should carry
daily messages during prime time... and present information on
the subject of AIDS."
</P>
<P>
The document said that 0.76 percent of South Africans were
infected in 1990, but since then the figure has increased more
than 21 times, to 16 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
According to a 1997 antenatal survey, 16 percent of women
attending antenatal clinics tested HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
This showed that the epidemic
was spreading across the country in an alarming rate.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 2.8 million of the 38 million population
have been infected with the virus and an average of 1,500 South
Africans are being infected every day.
</P>
<P>
"It is projected that by the year 2000, more than three
million people will be infected with the virus," the document
said.
</P>
<P>
The death of economically active people in the age group from
25 to 45 years has resulted in an estimated 8.2 million orphans
across the world, with 100,000 of these in South Africa's
Kwazulu-Natal province alone.
</P>
<P>
Kwazulu-Natal has the highest infection rate in South Africa.
According to the antenatal survey, 26.9 percent of women
attending antenatal clinics in the province were HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma attributed the fast
spread of the disease to poverty, lack of education, migrant
labor, high rates of sexually-transmitted diseases,
discrimination against infected people, and the breakdown of the
moral fiber of the society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
