<HEADLINE> FIFA Condemns Marseille Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- World governing body of football FIFA
condemned the violent clashes involving English fans at Marseille.
</P>
<P>
FIFA president Sepp Blatter said:"What can we do to combat these
individuals? We must get rid of them, stop them from entering
stadiums and return them to their countries. Football is a game and
must bring joy to the whole world."
</P>
<P>
In the routine FIFA briefing on Monday, FIFA spokesman Keith Cooper
said:"The fear is that the better-known ringleaders are still on their
way to Marseille. The fact that they are coming so late proves that
they are not interested in the football, only what comes after."
</P>
<P>
Some 1,900 policemen were patrolling Marseille, anticipating
more violence before the England-Tunisia match.
</P>
<P>
The violence was also condemned in England, but England soccer
officials denied the possibilities the England team withdraw from the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Brian Hayes, English Football Association security advisor,
said: "That's absolute rubbish. The England team have been training
for years, they've qualified, they're here as of right. This is
nothing to do with football, this is just sheer hooliganism and
drunkenness."
</P>
<P>
In the clashes at Marseille, 50 people had been arrested, at
least 30 of them from England and the others from Tunisia.
Altogether 37 people were injured, including an English man who had
his throat slashed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
