<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's IT Industry Lagging Behind: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Kenya remains east Africa's
largest information technology (IT) market valued at some 63.5
million U.S. Dollars but it is growing much slower than Uganda
and Tanzania, according to a Kenya-based IT firm's survey.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's IT sector is depressed with a growth rate of only four
percent compared to 25 percent and 18 percent respectively in
Tanzania and Uganda, the East African weekly quoted the survey by
the Telecom Forum Africa company as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The survey estimates east Africa's market investment this year
at 18 billion Kenya Shillings (285.7 million U.S. Dollars), of
which more than 50 percent is in Kenya, 30 percent in Tanzania
and below 20 percent in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The survey predicts that 30,000 personal computers will be
sold in the region by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
"The 18 billion Kenyan Shillings (to be invested in 1998) are half
of the estimated potential. The Zimbabwe, Botswana region has
close to three times the value of the east African market," said
Marcel Werner, the Managing Director of Telecom Forum Africa.
</P>
<P>
The collective IT market in the region in 1997 was 99 million
U.S. Dollars of which Kenya has 64 million U.S. Dollars with
Uganda 19.9 million U.S. Dollars and Tanzania 14.8 million
Dollars. The sum is expected to grow to 108 million U.S. Dollars
this year.
</P>
<P>
Werner cited the slow liberalization of parastatal companies
in the region as a cause of the depressed market as well as high
interest rates in Kenya, which discouraged private investors
from buying computers.
</P>
<P>
The survey puts the use of computers in Kenya's private sector
is at a growth rate of 4.3 percent compared to 30 percent in
Uganda and 36.9 percent in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The highest PC users listed in the survey are governments and
parastatals.
</P>
<P>
Of the manufacturing companies surveyed, Compaq PCs were
ranked as the market leader in the region followed by IBM. Compaq
sales were pegged at 43 percent in the market while IBM were at
28 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other brands varied in rank from country to country including
Hewlett-Packard, ICL, Dell and others.
</P>
<P>
Francis Hook, research manager at the company, said that clone or
copy computers which had infiltrated the market at the onset of
computer use have been phased out to a share of just two percent
by the big brands.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is the biggest computer vendor with 2,400 units sold in
1997 in the east African region while 1,250 and 900 units were
sold in Uganda and Tanzania respectively.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicates that computer software sales comprised 16
percent of the IT market value or 15.4 million U.S. Dollars in
1997. Kenya leads the spending on software followed by Uganda
and Tanzania. 
</P>
