<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Jumps Above 146 Yen in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar jumped over two yen in
Tokyo on Monday, hitting 146 yen for the first time in almost eight
years, as Japan's weak economy continued to weigh down the country's
currency.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 146.43-46 yen at 5 p.m. (local time), up
sharply from 144.63-66 yen at 9 a.m., and 144.15-25 yen late Friday in
New York.
</P>
<P>
During the day, the dollar hit a high of 146.58 yen, a level last
seen in Tokyo on August 22, 1990, when it went as high as 146.95 yen.
</P>
<P>
The bearishness toward the yen prevailed on pessimism about the
weak Japanese economy, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The yen-holding sentiment was further damaged during the day by the
plummet in stock markets around the region, including those of Hong
Kong, South Korea, Thailand and Tokyo, they added.
</P>
<P>
The key Nikkei average of Tokyo stock prices closed below the
15,000 line for the first time since January, ending at 14,825.17,
down 197.16 points from Friday.
</P>
<P>
Market players remain pessimistic as Japanese authorities appear
lethagic in taking measures to pump up the economy, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
With nothing changing in Japan, the yen will not fall sharply but
will continue to weaken against the dollar, an analyst said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
