<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Calls For Japan's Efforts to Stabilize Its Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese top Legislator Li Peng
today voiced the hope that the Japanese government and other
relative departments will adopt effective measures to stabilize
Japan's economy.
</P>
<P>
He said the financial crisis has produced a big impact on the
economies of Asian countries, and that the recent continued
devaluation of the Japanese Yen has imporsed a new pressure on the
economies in Asia, Li added.
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the Standing Committee of the Chinese National
People's Congress (NPC), made the remarks during a meeting with
former Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Nikaido Susumu here this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Li said Susumu had made special contributions to the
normalization of Sino-Japanese relations and expressed the hope
that Susumu and other Japanese friends will continue to dedicate
themselves to the growth of Sino-Japanese ties.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hope that the younger generations of both
China and Japan would inherit and carry forward the traditional
friendship shared by their elder generations.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that this year marks the 20th anniversary of
the signing of the Sino-Japanese Treaty of Peace and Friendship
and President Jiang Zemin is expected to pay a historically
significant visit to Japan this fall.
</P>
<P>
The relations between China and Japan are now at the critical
moment of inheriting the past and ushering into the future, Li
noted, adding that China values its good-neighborly ties with
Japan.
</P>
<P>
China and Japan should advance their cooperation and foster a
long-term, good-neighborly relationship on the basis of adhering
to the principles set in Sino-Japanese Joint Statement and
Sino-Japanese Treaty of Peace and Friendship, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Susumu said it is his 20th visit to China since 1972 and in
each previous visit he had been pleased to witness the great
achievements in the country's politics, economy, culture and other
fields.
</P>
<P>
He told Li that he will make continuous effort for the
development of Japan-China relations.
</P>
<P>
Susumu served as Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary in 1972, when
China and Japan normalized bilateral relations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
