<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Approves 51.9 Million Dollar Loan for Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC), the private sector arm of the World Bank, has
approved a loan of 51.9 million U.S. dollars to a private power
company in Bangladesh, said a World Bank press release reaching
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The approval was made early this month at the IFC board
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The loan would be provided through IFC's "A" loan of 22.5
million dollars and syndicated loan of 29.4 million dollars, it
said, adding these loans would be utilized to construct and
implement 110 mw barge mounted power plant to be set up in Kulna
district, 140 kilometers southwest of Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The 51.9-million-dollar loan is the largest ever provided to a
private sector project in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The first of the two barges Tiger 1 had arrived in the country
while the second one Tiger 2 would arrive in first week of July,
and the project was expected to go into production in the third
week of August, providing 110 mw much needed electricity to the
national grid, the release added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Recalls Envoy in Protest Against NATO Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Russia has recalled its military
envoy to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) to protest
against the alliance's military exercise in the vicinity of
Yugoslavia's Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The decision was made because NATO started a military air
exercise outside Kosovo without taking into consideration Russia's
opinion," the Interfax news agency quoted a source with the
Russian Defense Ministry as saying on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Lt.-Gen. Viktor Zavarzin, the Russian envoy to NATO, is
expected to return to Moscow on Tuesday, one day after the NATO
exercise begins in Albania and Macedonia on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Russia has repeatedly voiced its opposition to any military
settlement by NATO to the crisis in the Yugoslav region where
ethnic Albanians, who account for 90 percent of the population,
are demanding independence from the Yugoslav Republic of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 people have died there in clashes between
government forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army, the armed wing
of the Albanian independence movement.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, a Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman said it is
"of crucial importance" that the NATO exercise "not provoke either
the Albanian community in Kosovo or Belgrade to escalate (tension)
and give diplomats a possibility to work on settling the Kosovo
conflict," Interfax reports said.
</P>
<P>
"Political means must be used first of all for resolving the
conflict in Kosovo," Vladimir Rakhmanin, the spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav president Slobodan Milosevic will arrive in Moscow
later on Monday for a visit that is expected to focus on the
Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to meet Russian President Boris Yeltsin on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are putting great hopes on this meeting" Rakhmanin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
