<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Eric Tabarly, the legendary champion of boat sailing of France
and thrice champion of British Trans-Atlantic, died after falling
into the sea near Wales in the night from Friday to Saturday. He
fell from his most favorite saling boat ``Pen Duick 1,'' which his
father wanted to get rid of but was saved by himself.
</P>
<P>
-- The European Union summit to be opened Monday by British Prime
Minister Tony Blair in Cardiff, England, is not expected to make any
major decision because of the interior situation in Germany, which
will hold a general election in September 27. Because of his concern
for public opinion at home, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl will not
make any compromise or play a motor role at the summit.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Fighting between Serbian forces and Albanian separatists
resumed on Sunday in western Kosovo, on the eve of a large-scale
air force exercise of NATO countries in Albania and Macedonia. 80
war planes of NATO countries will join the exercise, which can be
a prelude to a military intervention in Kosovo if the Serb
offensive against ethnic Albanians continues.
</P>
<P>
-- Representatives from more than 100 countries will begin a
conference on Monday in Rome to seek an agreement on the creation of
a permanent international criminal court to try those who commit
genocide, war crimes and crime against humanity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
