<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue Tumbling in Tokyo as Yen Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices continued plunging in Tokyo
Monday with the key Nikkei index closing below the 15,000 line for the
first time in five months, as investors remained worried about the
declining yen and Japan's stagnant economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 197.16 points, or 1.31
percent, from last Friday's close to finish at 14,825.17. The index
last closed below 15,000 on January 13, when it ended at 14,755.94.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the major section, dropped 10.04 points or 0.85 percent to
1,167.21.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the First Section declined to an estimated 300 million
shares, well off from 818 million shares recorded Friday when special
quotation for futures prices was being set.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was Monday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
The nonstop fall of the yen against the dollar is causing
considerable concern on Asian stock markets and Tokyo is no exception.
The dollar hit the 145 yen level in Tokyo on Monday for the first time
since August 27, 1990.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the downward spiral of the Hong Kong market darkened
the already pessimistic mood among Tokyo-based investors.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,336 issues listed on the First Section, losers outpaced
gainers 679 to 430, with 177 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Countries Striving for Better Management of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 15 (Xinhua) -- A high-level seminar on managing
capital flows opened here Monday, with a call on Asian countries
to "promote a better understanding of policy responses required to
deal with large-scale capital flows".
</P>
<P>
In a keynote speech, Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai
Pantitchpakdi said, "The restoration of confidence should be our
top priority so that the influx of international capital resume."
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, recovery and growth are best achieved through
macroeconomic stabilization policies, coupled with structural
reforms, particularly through the liberalization of trade and
financial markets," Supachai said.
</P>
<P>
He said the movements of money and capital, as well as private
financial flows, cannot be left entirely to market forces without
incurring tremendous risks.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, we need a framework of surveillance and supervision
designed to prevent a recurrence of the present crisis without
hampering further liberalization of our economies," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two-day seminar was jointly organized by the U.N. Economic
and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP), the Asian
Development Bank, the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Among the topics for discussion are macroeconomic developments
and policy lessons, financial sector reforms in Asian economies,
sound practices to facilitate development of the financial sector
and corporate governance in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Drawing on the experience of the recent economic and financial
crises in the region, participants will identify ways and means to
manage capital flows to be able to reap their benefits while
avoiding their disruptive consequences," an ESCAP official said.
</P>
<P>
ESCAP Secretary-General Andrianus Mooy said the process of
globalization brings risks, especially considering the speed with
which private capital crosses borders.
</P>
<P>
"Unless such risks are managed effectively, the gains and
confidence achieved through years of hard work can be undermined
quickly and dramatically. This is precisely what happened in
several countries in East and Southeast Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Officials from nearly 30 countries took part in the seminar,
entitled "Managing Capital Flows: National and International
Dimensions". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors Urged to Boost Zambia's Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has called on the donor
community to offer financial support for creating a credit
facility to be accessed by the Zambians willing to invest in
tourism.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Zambia Daily Mail at the weekend, Tourism
Deputy Minister Cecil Holmes said that the Zambian government is
making efforts to ensure that the tourism industry do not
collapse, which is published by the newspaper Monday.
</P>
<P>
Holmes urged donors to emulate the World Bank which gave the
Ministry of Commerce about 40 million U.S. Dollars for a credit
scheme for small entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
"We would be very glad to see donors helping us in the same
way the World Bank did to the Ministry of Commerce," he said.
</P>
<P>
The creating of a credit facility will enable the Zambians to
invest in tourism and not to leave the business to foreigners
alone, the deputy minister added.
</P>
<P>
he stressed that it is important that the Zambians venture
into tourism because their profits will be ploughed back into
Zambia's economy rather than leaving it to the foreigners who
reinvest their returns in their countries of origin.
</P>
<P>
Holmes cited the inadequate information flow from Zambia to
the outside world as the major factor behind Zambia's bad
performance in the tourism sector.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to allocate more funds to the Zambia
National Tourist Board to enable it to adequately market the
country's tourism potential in other countries.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has vast potential of tourist resources such as wildlife
and unspoiled scenery, but its tourism is far from being
developed due to insufficient investment in the industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
