<HEADLINE> Economic, Trade Ties Offer Opportunities, Challenges  (1) by Xinhua correspondents Yang Guojun, Qian Tong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 15 (Xinhua) -- (Editor's Notes: Xinhua reporters
recently interviewed representatives from China's political,
economic and military circles in advance of U.S. President Bill
Clinton's coming visit to China later this month. The interviewees
responded with in-depth views concerning wide-ranging questions
related to Sino-U.S. exchanges and cooperation and approaches for
advancing the development of bilateral relations. Today's
exclusive interview with Zeng Peiyan, minister in charge of the
State Development Planning Commission, is the first in a series of
exclusive interview stories scheduled for release over the next
few days.)
</P>
<P>
China, the world's largest developing country, and the United
States, the world's largest developed nation, are confident and
capable of advancing bilateral economic and trade cooperation
which is "mutually beneficial and compatible with the advantages
of each side," according to Zeng Peiyan, the senior Chinese
official in charge of macroeconomic planning.
</P>
<P>
Zeng, minister in charge of the State Development Planning
Commission, underlined that bilateral ties "are not only in the
interests of the two peoples, but also play a due role in global
economic growth."
</P>
<P>
Sino-U.S. economic and trade ties are an integral part of "the
Sino-U.S. constructive strategic partnership," said Zeng, adding
that "related cooperation has ushered in a new era amidst constant
improving state-to-state relations over recent years, particularly
since Chinese President Jiang Zemin's U.S. visit last fall."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic, Trade Ties Offer Opportunities and Challenges  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"China's civil aviation sector alone has already ordered 387
Boeing and McDonnell Douglas aircraft valued at 18.3 billion
U.S. dollars. Some 60 percent of China's aircraft fleet was
manufactured in the United States," according to Zeng. He added
that the Shanghai Aviation Industrial Corp. and McDonnell Douglas,
which recently merged with Boeing, have jointly assembled 35 MD-82
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Zeng commented that the energy, environment and infrastructure
sectors in the two countries have also enjoyed "fruitful"
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese and U.S. governments signed the Proposal on
Sino-U.S. Energy and Environmental Cooperation and unveiled the
full-range of cooperation in the fields during the fall visit by
President Jiang.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by Zeng's commission shows that a large number
of Chinese power plants have imported power-generating equipment
from the United States. American enterprises have 17 bids from
Chinese power plants since 1992, with the total contract value of
approaching two billion U.S. dollars. Zeng further indicated that
Chinese and U.S. companies are expected to sign contracts for more
projects during coming US President Clinton's visit, including a
contract calling for the joint construction of the second-phase
project at the Wenzhou Power Plant in east China's Zhejiang
Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
