<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic, Trade Ties Offer Opportunities, Challenges  (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Moreover, American corporations have actively cooperated and
joined in the development of China's petroleum industry, with a
total of 98 contracts and agreements inked for both onshore and
offshore oil exploration and development. The State Development
Planning Commission and the U.S. departments of commerce and
energy plan to expand cooperation in the field by jointly hosting
the Sino-U.S. Oil and Natural Gas Forum and a conference on energy
fund-raising in the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
With regard to clean energy sphere, relevant companies from the
two nations are currently exploring coal-bed gas reserves in north
China's Shanxi Province, an area with abundant resources. "Certain
projects will generate investments of over a billion U.S. dollars
in the near future," said Zeng.
</P>
<P>
"China's economic growth and market potential obviously offer
sufficient room for furthering Sino-U.S. economic cooperation,"
said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said that China will invest 1,100 billion U.S. dollars in
infrastructure and import commodities valued at over 600 billion
dollars in the remaining three years of this century. In addition,
China will increase its installed generating capacity by 200
million kilowatts and increase its telephone switching capacity by
200 million lines over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed to the "unprecedented" development scale
in the petrochemical, electronics and automobile manufacturing
industries, as well as in the development of railways and
high-speed rail systems, urban light-track commuter systems,
highway and airport construction, aircraft manufacturing and
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
China's ongoing reforms are expected to generate a huge demand
for wide-ranging service industries, including the finance,
insurance, consulting, accounting and commodity wholesaling and
retail sectors.
</P>
<P>
The ability of American enterprises to use their technical
edge, competitive prices, highly developed services and the active
involvement of financial institutions to seize opportunities "will
depend on whether or not the United States adjusts its China
policy," said Zeng.
</P>
</TEXT>
