<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cargo Prices on Transatlantic Route Tumble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Cargo prices on the transatlantic
route have reached a 10-year low, reflecting a decline in overall
trade between sub-Saharan Africa and the United States in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
Goods and raw materials can now be transported in both
directions for as low as 4,000 U.S. Dollars for a 40-foot
container and 2,000 U.S. Dollars for a 20-foot box, the East
African weekly newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The rates represent a reduction of up to 50 percent from the
charges five years ago, said the report quoting articles from the
June edition of the Journal of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The volume of commerce was relatively high as recently as the
third quarter of 1997, but it has since dropped significantly for
a combination of reasons, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
One factor is the strength of the U.S. Dollar, which has made
American exports considerably more expensive for African buyers.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, they have turned to alternative sources in Asia.
The fall in value of many currencies there has enhanced the
competitiveness of Asian suppliers.
</P>
<P>
Soft global demand for both oil and gold has further
contributed to the slackening of U.S.-Africa trade.
</P>
<P>
"We are moving mining equipment at lower volumes right now
because gold prices internationally are so poor that there is no
incentive for the mines to undertake additional explorations,"
said Christian Holm, owner's representative for Torm Lines.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is almost the same for oil," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cocoa, traditionally an important commodity in west Africa's
trade with the U.S., is currently not exported at all, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Shipments will resume with the start of the cocoa harvest in
November, but prices are expected to remain comparatively low.
Cocoa rates have fallen by as much as 50 percent during the past
few years.
</P>
<P>
Carriers on the Africa-U.S. route can achieve significant
savings by transshipping via Europe, but that option results in
much longer transit times, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Cargo sent directly between Africa and the U.S. arrives in
three to four weeks, while transshipments through European ports
can take twice as long.
</P>
<P>
Air freight offers a speedier but much more expensive option
for American businesses shipping high-priority goods to Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, even by air, door-to-door delivery time may be as
long as a full week, according to Bruce Rea, Vice-President of
the Georgia-based arm of a South African manufacturer of lorries
used in construction.
</P>
<P>
Rea said that he relies on air freight for "urgent traffic"
such as air conditioning units and radiators.
</P>
<P>
It was said that some African governments are making progress
in privatizing port facilities. But major obstacles must still
be overcome before foreign investors agree to share in the risks
associated with these privatization initiatives.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration has made strong efforts to interest
American investors in opportunities at African ports that are
being privatized, the report claimed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
