<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Tower Semiconductor and Motorola are holding talks
on setting up a joint venture in Israel to produce semiconductors,
the daily newspaper Haaretz reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It said the two companies based in the United States are
estimated to invest about 1.2 billion U.S. dollars in the project.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's industrial exports stood at 1.61 billion
dollars in May, 4.6 percent more than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Most of the growth was gained in the sectors of medical
equipment and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's export of fruits and vegetables increased by
4 percent in 1997 compared with that in 1996, the Jordan Times
newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The United Arab Emirates topped the list of importers, which
was followed by Kuwait, Lebanon, Qatar, Bahrain, Saudi Arabia,
Oman and Iraq, Director General of the Jordanian Agricultural
Marketing Organization Salem Lawzi said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Only 1.3 percent of the total exports in 1997 went to non-Arab
countries, Lawzi added.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the increase to his organization's continued
efforts to open more markets for the kingdom's agricultural
products.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The domestic tourism in Saudi Arabia has been
growing annually by 10 percent, the Saudi English-language daily
Arab News reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
General Manager of the Saudi Public Transport Co. Abdulaziz
Al-Ohali attributed the growth to the accomplishment of major
infrastructural projects and quality service provided by public
tourism and transport services.
</P>
<P>
Abdulaziz said that some major infrastructural projects, such
as hotels and other accommodation facilities, have been completed
in well-known scenic spots.
</P>
<P>
Besides, media's support in highlighting tourism attractions
has also contributed to the tourism development, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
