<HEADLINE> English Fans Go on Rampage in Marseille </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MARSEILLE, France, June 15 (Xinhua) -- About 200 English fans
rioted Marseille on Sunday night, smashing shops and damaging cars on
the eve of a World Cup game here.
</P>
<P>
Police equipped with the helmets and shields fired tear gas to
contain the violence, which led the arrest of around 30 English
supporters.
</P>
<P>
At least two injured English fans were described as in serious
condition in local hospital while about twenty other fans suffered
minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
This was the scenes that the French authories feared most before
the World Cup kicked off last Wednesday and the riots here eventually
caused the cancellation of a free concert in the city Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The trouble started on Saturday night but spilled over to Sunday
when rival fans from England and Tunisia clashed with each other,
hurling bottles and exchanged verbal abuses.
</P>
<P>
Their soccer squads are to face each other in Group G in the World
Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
Marseille press lamented the early breakout of hooliganism in the
five-week competition, with major newspaper La Provence crying "The
Hooligans Have been Unleashed Already".
</P>
<P>
In London, British Sports Minister Tony Banks described the
trouble-makers "drunken, brain-dead louts," while Home Secretary Jack
Straw said French police had full support of the British government.
</P>
<P>
Over 10,000 English fans were expected to pour into the city for
the match. On the other side, the French authorities planned to
deploy almost 2,000 police officers and 100 anti-riot CRS policemen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
