<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa Faces Maize Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African Development
Community (SADC) countries will have a maize deficit of 1.35
million tons for the 1998/99 marketing year, according to a
latest SADC bulletin.
</P>
<P>
The daily Herald Monday quoted the bulletin of the SADC
Regional Early Warning Unit as saying that the SADC member
countries are expected to harvest 16.73 million tons of maize in
this season against last season's 17 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The unit attributes the decline in total maize harvest to
erratic rainfalls and reduced plantings in some countries and
long spells of overcast weather in others.
</P>
<P>
Current assessments indicated substantial maize deficits in
Zimbabwe with 646,000 tons, Zambia 209,000 tons, Angola 322,000
tons, Namibia 140,000 tons, and Lesotho 196,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
However, on individual basis, Mozambique, South Africa and
Tanzania are projected to have maize surpluses of 134,000 tons,
386,000 tons and 89,000 tons respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
