<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. Africa to Set up Joint Military Liaison Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Kenya,
Tanzania and Uganda, the three members of the East Africa
Cooperation (EAC), are to establish a joint military liaison
office at the EAC secretariat in Arusha, northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The move will be endorsed by the defense ministers of the
three countries at their next meeting in Nairobi on June 19, the
East African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi talks will be preceded by a meeting of the chiefs
of defense forces in Arusha on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the defence liaison office is in
accordance with a memorandum of understanding which the three
countries signed in April.
</P>
<P>
"We expect (EAC) member states to appoint defence officials
who will be on secondment from their defence forces for a
specified time. We expect them to be appointed as soon as the
modalities have been worked out, and their ministers approved,"
said EAC Executive Secretary Francis Muthaura.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations of the nine-member team will be submitted
for discussion by the chiefs of defence on June 17, and for
approval by ministers of defence two days later in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Muthaura said the liaison office is intended to intensify
cooperation between the member states with regard to defence.
</P>
<P>
The three countries will carry out joint training, security,
disaster handling operations and coordination of various other
defence-related matters.
</P>
<P>
A joint military exercise involving about 2,000 soldiers from
the three states and 120 U.S. army trainers started on June 2 and
will end on June 27 in northern Kenya.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
