<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK, Australian Ties Important: Tung Chee Hwa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, Australia, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Hong Kong Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa stressed here Monday the importance of the
relationship between Hong Kong and Australia, saying the purpose
of his ongoing visit is to make sure the relationship is further
enhanced.
</P>
<P>
"Taking this opportunity of being here in Australia, and here
in Sydney I also have chances to discuss with many (political and
business) leaders how important this Hong Kong and Australian
relationship is," said Tung, chief executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China,
who arrived here Sunday morning on a three-day visit to Australia.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The purpose of my trip is to make sure this
relationship is further enhanced because it is not just the trade
and investment relationship, it is also people's relationship:
thousands of (Hong Kong) students are studying here."
</P>
<P>
"We have many (people) who migrated to this great city living
here. Equally, there're 30,000 Australians working in Hong Kong,"
he told reporters at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said late last
month that Hong Kong is Australia's eighth largest export market
and fourth largest source of investment.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, more than 13,770 students from Hong Kong came to
Australia for full-time study, the fourth largest source of
overseas students for Australia, Downer said.
</P>
<P>
Asked how soon Hong Kong economy would recover from recession,
Tung said the economy would continue to be difficult for the
future, but in the longer term... it would rebound strongly.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the rumor that the Chinese government might
back
away from its pledge not to devalue its currency Renminbi, Tung
said, "I cannot see a devaluation of the Renminbi at all".
</P>
<P>
He explained that the leadership in China had made it very
clear
that they would not devalue the currency and "I have every belief
that this policy will not change."
</P>
<P>
"From the economic point of view...looking at the economic
fundamentals... Chinese exports increased in the first quarter of
this year by about 12 percent. And it (China) had a trade surplus
of 8.7 billion (U.S.) dollars," he added. "Foreign direct
investment in the first quarter also increased by close to 10
percent...All these fundamental figures ...tell you that
devaluation is not in the cards."
</P>
<P>
"I think there is no need for China to devalue its currency
both politically and economically," he said.
</P>
<P>
In response to another question, Tung said, "Australia has been
a very successful, tolerant society, which practices
multi-culturalism. This is where Australia's strength is. And I
cannot imagine Australia deviating from this very successful
practice of the past."
</P>
<P>
Tung left Sydney Monday afternoon for Melbourne, where he is
scheduled to meet with Australian Prime Minister John Howard and
Deputy Prime Minister and Trade Minister Tim Fischer and other
senior federal and state officials Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The HK chief executive is scheduled to leave Melbourne
Wednesday for a three-day visit to New Zealand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
