<HEADLINE> Thai Police Crack Down on World Cup Gambling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Thai police Monday said they had
rounded up 70 bookmakers and 80 punters in a crackdown on World
Cup gambling.
</P>
<P>
Millions of baht (about tens of thousands of U.S. dollars) was
also seized in the raids since the tournament began in France last
Wednesday, an officer at the operations center of a special World
Cup anti-gambling task force noted.
</P>
<P>
All gambling outside horse-racing and lotteries is illegal in
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Professional gamblers had set aside an average of 65,170 baht
each, against 46,160 baht in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 1,012 people found students were ready to wager
an average 5, 550 baht, an increase of 38.8 percent from four
years ago. 
</P>
