<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Minister On Poverty Alleviation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Fifty percent of Bangladesh's 127
million people are still living below the poverty line, press
reports said Monday.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Minister for Local Government, Rural
Development and Cooperatives Zillur Rahman while addressing a
workshop on strategies for poverty eradication here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Poverty alleviation was the most vital part of the national
development policies, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that poverty alleviation could be achieved through
expansion of productive employment and income generating
activities, human resources development, larger participation of
women and youth in the development process, building of physical
infrastructure in the rural areas and development of rural
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The government was committed to evolving a permanent and
fruitful method of service system to improve the condition of the
rural poor, he stated.
</P>
<P>
The fifth 5-Year Plan (1998-2002) took a comprehensive view of
rural poverty, he said, adding the government had allocated 87
billion taka (about 1.89 billion U.S. dollars) in the current
5-year plan as against only 19.6 billion taka (about 426 million
dollars) allocated in the previous 5-year plan.
</P>
<P>
The gigantic task of rural development required well-defined
strategies and concerted efforts by efficient organizations such
as ministries as well as other government and non-government
agencies, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Food production of the country had almost reached the level of
self-sufficiency, population growth had slowed down, access to
safe drinking water had increased, primary education was expanding
rapidly with significant increase in literacy rate and rural women
were gaining economic and social freedom, he told the workshop.
</P>
<P>
These had been achieved through decades of endeavors by both
government and non-government organizations, he added.
</P>
<P>
As an agriculture-based country, Bangladesh has over 80 percent
of people living in the rural areas where the people living below
the poverty line account for more than 80 percent of the total
number of the poor people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
