<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, June 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO -- The Japanese government has provided Sri Lanka 1.77
million U.S. dollars worth of agricultural implements to boost
food production in the country, according to Agricultural Ministry
sources here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The implements include 40 tractors, 21 tine tillers, 61 disc
ploughs, 100 paddy harvesting machines, two combine harvesting
machines and eight double cabs, the sources said. Japan has also
provided Sri Lanka with free fertilizer and helped the country
install a plant quarantine center and a plant genetic center.
(Sri Lanka-Japan-Aid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Central Bank of the Philippines has approved
stricter rules for the entry of new banks to strengthen the
banking industry and protect it from further internal shocks,
Business World reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Monetary Board, the highest policy-making
body of the central bank, wanted to encourage only the better
industry participants by tightening entry and competency
qualification criteria. (Philippines-Banks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The Asian financial crisis is expected to slow down the
world economic growth this year by as much as one percent, a
survey conducted by the German Ifo economic research institute
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey of 420 multinational companies and
economic institutes in 66 countries, the world economy is expected
to grow by 2.5 percent this year. Without the Asian crisis, the
growth rate could be one percentage point higher, Ifo said.
(World Economy) 
</P>
