<HEADLINE> Thai Railways to Have Computerized Ticketing System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The State Railway of Thailand
(SRT) will have its new on-line ticketing service launched in
August, the Bangkok Post reporter here Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the 500-million-baht (11.6 million
U.S. dollar) seat ticketing and reservation system (Star 2)
project would boost ticket sales and modernize the way booking is
handled.
</P>
<P>
Preeda Pramote, the private company which won the bidding of
the project, will invest in the installation of the computerized
system and in return, it will be allowed to collect income from
the share of ticket sales over a 10-year concession.
</P>
<P>
SRT officials said the new system would speed up booking and
make the service more convenient for passengers, adding it would
also plug the leakage of state revenue through unmonitored ticket
sales.
</P>
<P>
The new system will also record important data which enables
the SRT to cater to the customers' demand more efficiently, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Star 2, which will replace the tedious manual
reservation-making, would hook up 446 railway stations nationwide.
</P>
<P>
By August, the installation will likely be completed in 103
stations and elsewhere by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
