<HEADLINE> Japan Gives Sri Lanka Agricultural Implements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
provided Sri Lanka 1.77 million U.S. dollars worth of agricultural
implements to boost food production in the country, according to
Agricultural Ministry sources here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The implements include 40 tractors, 21 tine tillers, 61 disc
ploughs, 100 paddy harvesting machines, two combine harvesting
machines and eight double cabs, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Japan has also provided Sri Lanka with free fertilizer and
helped the country install a plant quarantine center and a plant
genetic center.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Sri Lanka last year launched a successful food
drive in response to the United Nations' warning of a food crisis
in year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The food drive has resulted in a bumper paddy harvest of 1.88
million metric tons of paddy, an achievement recognized by the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has also implemented a special program to produce
high quality agricultural goods at low costs and increase
production using new technologies to produce surplus for the
international market.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government supplied Sri Lanka irrigation machinery
 worth about 8.7 million U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that the Japanese aid will serve Sri Lanka
much in her effort to produce more food and face the challenge in
2000. 
</P>
