<HEADLINE> Thai Hospitals Open Door for Foreign Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Under the pressure of serious
financial problems, many private hospitals in Thailand have to
begin seeking foreign partners for survival, the Bangkok Post said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the first foreign investment in a
Thai private hospital is expected within the next few months.
</P>
<P>
Deputy chief executive administrator of Bangkok General
Hospital (BGH) Dr. Krittavith Lertutsahakul informed that the
hospital was negotiating with foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Investors from Singapore, Australia and Sweden have expressed
an interest in investing in private Thai hospitals, the newspapers
said.
</P>
<P>
Private hospitals, expanded rapidly in past years, are now
finding it difficult to maintain their services because of the
economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
More and more people prefer buying over-the-counter drugs to
going to hospitals for medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
Private hospitals are faced with three alternatives to survive,
namely staff reductions, greater specialization, or finding a
foreign partner.
</P>
<P>
Krittavith said he believed foreign participation would improve
the standard of services at hospitals due to foreigners'
experience and know-how. 
</P>
</TEXT>
