<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Forestry Rises 1.3 Percent in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's forestry rose 1.3 percent
in its production in the 1997-98 fiscal year ended March,
according to the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The rise was due to a slight increase in production of hardwood
and other forest products, said a report on the country's
financial, economic and social conditions issued by the Ministry
of National Planning and Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
The production of hardwood increased to 195,694 cubic meters
from 192,440 cubic meters, fuel wood to 255,690 cubic meters from
251,021 cubic meters and charcoal to 254,700 cubic meters from
212,250 cubic meters, while that of teak decreased to 283,000
cubic meters from 287,000 cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The export quantity of the country's teak went to 215,448 cubic
meters in the fiscal year, while that of hardwood stood at 142,915
cubic meters, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar undertook some measures in the 1997-98 to enable
long-term commercial extraction of its forest products without
depleting the forest resources, ensuring environmental
conservation, ecological preservation and promotion of
manufacture of value-added finished wood products.
</P>
<P>
In forest conservation, total reserved forest area increased to
106,247 square kilometers in 1997-98 from 2,358 square kilometers
in the previous fiscal year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
During the fiscal year, plantation of 900,000 teak trees and
2.8 million hardwood trees as well as 11.2 million saplings by the
public were carried out, it said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is rich in forest resources with forest covering about
51 percent of its total land area. The output value of the
forestry sector accounts for 1 percent of the country's gross
domestic product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
