<HEADLINE> Tamil Rebel Hideout Discovered In Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 15 (Xinhua) -- A special Police team Sunday
discovered a Tamil rebel hideout in Kandy, the capital of Central
province of Sri Lanka, police sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the hideout was in the thick jungles of
Bowelawatte in Kandy from which they recovered 1,526 rounds of
live ammunition, several suicide kits and 600 high powered bullets
used for the suicide kits.
</P>
<P>
They believe that the hideout was a fairly major camp of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) and that both men and
women cadres had lived here.
</P>
<P>
Several black belts used for the suicide kits and an 18 inch
pipe used to fix bombs were also discovered there.
</P>
<P>
The ammunition and suicide kits, the sources said, indicated
that they had been brought for a planned attack on either VIPs or
some government installation.
</P>
<P>
Further investigations are continuing while the jungles are
being scoured for more evidence, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting a war against the government
for a separate state in the north and east of the island country
since 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
