<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Economist Urges US, Japan to Solve Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 15 (Xinhua) -- A prominent Thai economist have
called on the United States and Japan to coordinate their
macro-economic policies to solve the current economic crisis in
Asia, the Nation reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The United States should expand its money supply or cut
interest rates, while Japan should spend more through a greater
budget deficit, Teerana Bhongmakapat, associate professor at
Chulalongkorn University's economics faculty, suggested over the
weekend when commenting on the free-fall of the Japanese yen
during the past week.
</P>
<P>
The sharp slide in the yen and the sharp appreciation of the
U.S. dollar have come about because both countries have been
focusing on their own domestic economic objectives, the Nation
quoted Teerana as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the Asian financial crisis has already spread to other
parts of the world, and a second Asian crisis is set to be
unleashed because of the weak yen, he said.
</P>
<P>
If the world's two biggest economies do not adopt international
economic objectives, a global financial crisis will come soon in
which Europe and the United States will not escape unhurt, the
economist warned.
</P>
<P>
Teerana suggested the U.S. Federal Reserve buy more domestic
bonds or foreign assets, which will result in injection of money
supply into the market and could bring the interest rates down.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Japanese government should expand government
expenditure by running a greater fiscal deficit to stimulate
domestic demand, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government should sell bonds in the domestic
market to get funds which will push up interest rates and curb
capital outflows, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
