<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulls Beats Jazz 4-2 to Win NBA Finals for Sixth Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordon scored a series
high 45 points to help the Chicago Bulls beat the Utah Jazz 87-86
in the NBA Finals to wrap up the series 4-2 in Salt Lake City on
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
It is the sixth championship the Bulls have won in this decade,
and it is also their second third staight victory in NBA history.
Ironicly, it is also a repeat defeat for the Jazz who lost last
season's series with the same score.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, perhaps the greatest NBA player ever, rose at the
crucial occasion with 5.2 seconds left, burying a jumper to lead
the score 87-86. The sixth time NBA Finals MVP had a tremendous
show in his "last dance" tonight, turning the whole game to a solo
show.
</P>
<P>
Karl Malone hit 31 points to lead Utah's scorers.
</P>
<P>
With Scottie Pippen hobbled by a back injury, the Bulls had to
rely on Jordan completely.
</P>
<P>
With the Jazz led 86-85 and the time was left 15 seconds,
Jordan poked the ball away from Malone and created a golden chance
for the Bulls to turn the tide.
</P>
<P>
Jordan dribbled to the foul line, dropping his defender, and
leaped up to hit his winning jumper. The shot found the bottom of
the net dramatically with only 5.2 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
The Jazz still had one more chance, but John Stockton's
three-pointer effort fell just short before the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
Jordan had a 15-of-35 shooting, including three shots beyond
the arc. His highest score was 55 in 1993 when the Bulls played
against Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was rewarded with his sixth finals MVP trophy. Now, the
world is waiting Jordan's decision: will the greatest basketballer
want to retire after this brilliant win? 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
