<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Expectation from Clinton's Hometown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 14 (Xinhua) -- They are modest and amicable,
warmhearted and hospitable. When talking about President Bill
Clinton's upcoming visit to China, they feel proud of their former
governor and curious to know more about that Asian country.
</P>
<P>
"The world is too small," said local government officials,
educators and businessmen who were happy to meet the Chinese press
in Littlerock, where Clinton governed Arkansas for 12 years and
campaigned hard for his way to the White House. "A lot of people,
if not all, in his hometown will certainly watch TV coverage of
Bill's China trip," confirmed Skip Rutherford, director of the
Presidential Library Project.
</P>
<P>
"China is still a mystery to many people in the United States
and I think we should try to learn more about other countries
which might not share our belief, instead of trying to impose our
ideas," said the president's staunch supporter, who was believed
to contribute a lot to his success in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Skip said that the first thing he wants to do is to finance his
children's travels aboard, including trips to China, to enrich
their knowledge, if he's better off. He believes that President
Clinton's trip to China will help people understand the mystery
better.
</P>
<P>
Eventually it is no longer a mystery for all. Jim Dailey, mayor
of Littlerock, has travelled to China twice since his city
established a sistership with Chang Chun, provincial capital of Ji
Lin in Northeastern China, in 1994. He was astonished to notice at
his first trip that a sign of welcome held high by his Chinese
host at the airport wronged his city as "Little Stone" in
Chinese. But when he flew to Chang Chun for the second time and
visited an elementary school, he was very much touched to hear
pupils greeting him "Dailey, Welcome" in English.
</P>
<P>
Sharon Piest, Secretary of State of Arkansas, hasn't been able
to visit China so far. However, she knows the importance of
engaging that country in every field and supports Clinton's
summit meeting with Chinese President Jiang Zemin. "It is in the
interests of both side to understand each other better and
cooperate with each other better," said Sharon, who ranks third in
the Arkansas government.
</P>
<P>
Marolyn Chambers-Dorman, vice president of Riceland Lecithin
Division, shared the belief. She traveled to Shanghai recently to
assess the China's market potential for Lecithin, a nutriment
extracted from soybean. The conclusion was encouraging and she was
quick to realize that "Shanghai is a real business metropolis like
Tokyo and New York." She is now awaiting delegations from
Shanghai and Heilongjiang to explore the possibility of
establishing joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
Winrock International, a non-profit institute dedicated to
agriculture development worldwide, is working on The Lead21
Program with various Chinese partners. The program builds on
China's existing Ph.D. programs in agricultural economics by
strengthening course work and applied research at participating
institutes. "We lately opened an office in Beijing," said Mary
Laurie, public affairs director.
</P>
<P>
Academic exchanges are also gaining momentum, as described by
William Goolsby, Donaghey Dean of Business Administration of
Arkansas University. His faculty agreed in May to accept 35
students from Tianjin University of Finance and Economics this
year as a first step toward closer cooperative ties.
</P>
<P>
Arkansas University also set up a China-America center for
statistics and economic research, providing opportunities for both
Chinese and U.S. scholars to work together. The center has
launched a research program on cotton infestations and diseases in
Xinjiang and other places in Western China. The university's
Fulbright College of Arts and Sciences is also seeking expanded
China programs. "We are ready to accept Chinese students in
hundreds and to expand exchanges with our Chinese counterparts,"
said Mark Cory, associate dean.
</P>
<P>
Dave Mcmahen of Impuls company based in Russellville sounded
confident to succeed in his joint venture with China's Sundiro.
Motorcycle parts would be shipped from China's Hainan province and
assembled in Arkansas before the Chinese products go to the
American markets. "It is the first Chinese foothold in Arkansas so
far and I'm sure it will be enough competitive," said Dave at a
construction site. The plant will be operational in September.
</P>
<P>
People in Hope, Clinton's birthplace, are more enthusiastic
about the president's trip to China. "Bill is intelligent and
smart enough to tide over the controversy," said Joe Purvis, a
lawyer and President Clinton's childhood friend. He was referring
to the pressure brought on the president not to visit China this
time.
</P>
<P>
"That's really great," said in one tone Clinton's relatives,
friends and mayor Ramsey who gathered at a humble two-storey house
where President Clinton grew until age of four. They are anxious
to know if First Lady Hillary will be going with the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
