<HEADLINE> NATO Planes Ready for Show of Strength in Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 14 (Xinhua) -- About 40 NATO warplanes are waiting
at an airbase in northern Italy for an air exercise to
begin early Monday morning over Albania and Macedonia, which
border the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, NATO officials said.
</P>
<P>
The operation, code-named Determined Falcon involving nine
countries, is intended to step up pressure on Yugoslav President
Slobaodan Milosevic to negotiate an end to his conflict with
ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of Kosovo's population.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by NATO in Brussels on
Saturday said the operation is to demonstrate NATO's "capacity to
rapidly stage a show of strength" in the Balkans region.
</P>
<P>
The exercise will include fighters, reconnaissance planes,
airborne early warning systems, air refueling tankers and
helicopters, operating from the Aviano airbase north of Venice and
from an American amphibious task force in the Adriatic Sea.
</P>
<P>
Countries sending aircraft for the manoeuvre are Belgium,
Britain, Denmark, France, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, Turkey
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
NATO's action comes as the conflict in Kosovo is turning
increasingly violent.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 people have died and some 65,000 people been made
refugees since the Serb-led government of the Yugoslav federation
began a military crackdown on the ethnic Albanian independence
movement in Kosovo early this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
