<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Tightens Rules for Entry of New Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
has approved stricter rules for the entry of new banks to
strengthen the banking industry and protect it from further
internal shocks, Business World reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Monetary Board, the highest policy-making
body of the central bank, wanted to encourage only the better
industry participants by tightening entry and competency
qualification criteria.
</P>
<P>
The Monetary Board approved in its regular meeting last week
three additional requirements in the revised guidelines for
establishing new banks, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the new requirements, each shareholder of the new
bank must submit the statement of income and expenses for the last
three calendar years as proof of sources of income to support net
worth growth.
</P>
<P>
They must also present evidences of asset ownership such as
bank certification, passbook, certificate of time deposit, bond or
stock certificate, tax declaration and others.
</P>
<P>
The shareholders of a foreign bank must also submit
certifications by the home country's supervisory authority that it
has no objection to the investment in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The supervisory authority must also provide adequate
information on the foreign bank and its subsidiaries to the
Philippine central bank to the extent allowed under existing laws.
</P>
<P>
By ensuring that a new bank has good financial backgrounds and
track records, the central bank hopes to prevent situations in
which management or shareholders use the bank as their personal
money bag, central bank governor Gabriel Singson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0228 </DOCNO>
