<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, June 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel stressed on Sunday
that any NATO military intervention in the Serbian province of
Kosovo must first be approved by the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Sunday, Kinkel said that the planned
NATO aerial manoeuvres in Albania and the Republic of Macedonia on
Monday could go without U.N. mandate because it takes place in two
countries which have participated in the NATO program of
"Partnership for Peace" and which have given green light to the
exercise.
</P>
<P>
However, in case of a NATO military intervention in Kosovo or
its airspace, an approval by the U.N. Security Council was
required, Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
By contrast, U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen said
earlier that a U.N. approval of a NATO intervention in Kosovo was
"desirable, but not necessary." (Germany-Kosovo-Military
Intervention)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MARSEILLE -- At least 20 English and Tunisian soccer fans have
been arrested after fighting broke out again here following
Saturday night disturbances.
</P>
<P>
Riot police moved in and fired tear gas to break up hundreds of
fans from the two countries in the port area of this southern city.
</P>
<P>
Some English fans threw bottles at the police, who intervened
after a group of Tunisian fans moving toward the English
supporters were greeted with projectiles.
</P>
<P>
About 10,000 English fans and thousands of Tunisian supporters were
expected to pour into the city for Monday's game. (World
Cup-English, Tunisian Fans)
