<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Edible Oil Abstracted from Tea Seeds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 15 (Xinhua) -- After eight years of experiments,
a farmer in east China's Zhejiang Province has developed the
technique of abstracting edible oil from tea seeds, which
otherwise would be thrown away.
</P>
<P>
The technique, pioneered by Fang Shunzhong of Jinhua City, is
purely physical and can abstract 14 kg of fine edible oil of a
transparent yellow color out of 100 kg of tea seeds.
</P>
<P>
Though the idea of abstracting edible oil from tea seeds is not
new, before Fang's innovation, oil abstracted from tea seeds was
turbidly black and bitter in taste, and therefore not suitable for
use in foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
"Fang's innovation means a lot to tea farmers," said a
spokesman for the Jinhua Lanxiang Green Food Co. Ltd., in which
Fang is a shareholder.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has 1.4 million ha of tea plantations,
yielding more than 800 million kg of tea seeds annually. Only a
few of the seeds are kept for procreation, and the rest are thrown
away.
</P>
<P>
The company is so far the only user of Fang's technique. It
has turned out the first batch of oil, which is expected to be
marketed at 80-90 yuan per kg.
</P>
<P>
Fang, as a tea grower himself, did the research individually,
using 900,000 yuan of his own money.
</P>
<P>
An appraisal report from the China Quality Supervision and
Inspection Center shows that the various indices of Fang's oil
exceed those of the national first-degree edible oil standard.
</P>
<P>
Nutritionists in the Zhejiang food hygiene supervision
department have affirmed that the oil is cholesterol-free and
effective for eliminating non-saturated fatty acid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Implementing Sustainable Development Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 15 (Xinhua) -- China will adopt a wide range of
measures to advance implementation of a sustainable development
strategy, said Pan Wencan, deputy head of the national leading
group for the China 21st Century Agenda, at a symposium held in
this central Chinese city.
</P>
<P>
The measures will include spreading ecological agriculture,
promoting clean production in industrial enterprises, improving
the ecological environment in some selected areas such as major
river valleys, intensifying construction of ecological
shelterbelts and protection of animal and plant resources in
northeast China, and concentrating efforts on developing and
utilizing clean energy, said Pan.
</P>
<P>
China drafted the China 21st Century Agenda in March 1994,
implemented a plan on priority projects to be finished under the
agenda and compiled a national report on China's sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
So far, 25 provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities have
set up their respective leading groups for the China 21st Century
Agenda. Some localities have even worked out their respective
regional 21st century agendas or action plans, as well as priority
projects.
</P>
<P>
China regards its sustainable development strategy as a basic
state policy for the modernization drive, and has urged
different localities and relevant departments to implement the China
21st Century Agenda by writing the guidelines of the agenda into local
economic and social development plans, as well as including the
spirit of the agenda in government decision-making and
management mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
The country has so far designated 50 counties as national-level
bases to experiment with ecological agriculture. In addition, 29
industrial enterprises have realized clean production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Tightens Rules for Entry of New Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
has approved stricter rules for the entry of new banks to
strengthen the banking industry and protect it from further
internal shocks, Business World reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Monetary Board, the highest policy-making
body of the central bank, wanted to encourage only the better
industry participants by tightening entry and competency
qualification criteria.
</P>
<P>
The Monetary Board approved in its regular meeting last week
three additional requirements in the revised guidelines for
establishing new banks, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the new requirements, each shareholder of the new
bank must submit the statement of income and expenses for the last
three calendar years as proof of sources of income to support net
worth growth.
</P>
<P>
They must also present evidences of asset ownership such as
bank certification, passbook, certificate of time deposit, bond or
stock certificate, tax declaration and others.
</P>
<P>
The shareholders of a foreign bank must also submit
certifications by the home country's supervisory authority that it
has no objection to the investment in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The supervisory authority must also provide adequate
information on the foreign bank and its subsidiaries to the
Philippine central bank to the extent allowed under existing laws.
</P>
<P>
By ensuring that a new bank has good financial backgrounds and
track records, the central bank hopes to prevent situations in
which management or shareholders use the bank as their personal
money bag, central bank governor Gabriel Singson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
