<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Prepares for Flood Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 15 (Xinhua) -- People in all parts of China are
busy making preparations for the upcoming flood season.
</P>
<P>
An anti-flood shock brigade has been formed at the construction
site of the Xiaolangdi Project, where the Yellow River was dammed
last October.
</P>
<P>
The upper coffer dam of the Xiaolangdi Project has been
completed, and the intake tower has reached the level of 220
m. Work on two of the three basins are ready for flood water, with
the remaining one to be finished in the latter half of this month.
</P>
<P>
In Jingjiang City, on the most dangerous section of the Yangtze
River, six million people have been organized to reinforce
embankments on the river.
</P>
<P>
By the end of May, the city had prepared 640,000 cu m of
stones, 290,000 sandbags, 670,000 straw sacks and other
materials needed for fighting floods.
</P>
<P>
They have reinforced a total area of 22 million cu m of
dangerous embankments, an all-time high, repaired 66 reservoirs
and built 335 water gates and 45 pumping stations.
</P>
<P>
North China's Hebei Province has invested 1.38 billion yuan to
build new or repair existing flood-control projects.
</P>
<P>
A program-controlled telecom system has been built covering 11
large reservoirs in the Taihang Mountains in Hebei Province, which
has over 200 flood-emergency teams, involving 2.2 million people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 60,000 trucks and excavators are working day
and night along the Haihe River to reinforce its dykes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
