<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jilin Aims for Nine Percent Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The authorities in Northeast
China's Jilin Province have pledged to work harder to ensure a
nine percent growth in the province's gross domestic product (GDP)
this year.
</P>
<P>
This year the province is also set to realize a ten percent
increase in revenue, and to ensure that inflation is lower than
three percent, besides resuming agricultural production level
before the 1997 drought, which caused a loss of 3.5 billion kg of
grain.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Dejiang, who has been re-elected as secretary of the
Jilin Provincial Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC),
told delegates to a provincial party congress to bear in mind this
year's economic growth target, eight major tasks to be
accomplished, and to make careful plans for this year's
overall work.
</P>
<P>
The eight major tasks are: achieving successful agricultural
production, making fresh progress in the industrialization of
agriculture, turning loss-making industrial manufacturers into
profit-making ones, doing a good job of re-employment and properly
arranging the lives of laid-off workers, expanding reforms of
grain purchasing and marketing, developing the export-oriented
economy, fostering high-tech industries and vigorously expanding
the private economy to create new area of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Officials all over the province have expressed full confidence
about meeting the nine percent economic growth target.
</P>
<P>
Li Shu, mayor of this provincial capital, said Changchun will
work for a 10.3 percent economic growth by spurring local demand
and increasing investment in basic industries this year, while
Liu Yongxin, party secretary of Liaoyuan City, promised a 12
percent growth in the city's economy.
</P>
<P>
China has set its economic growth rate at eight percent this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
