<DOCNO> XIE19980615.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Real Estate Investment Remains Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Overseas investment in real
estate in the Pudong New Area here, the most vigorous economic
development zone in China, has been affected by the financial
crisis in Southeast Asia, "but only to a limited degree," said Li
Zhanjun, an official at the Pudong Reform and and Development
Institute.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Li said that his
conclusion is based on a detailed analysis of major Pudong
projects financed by Japan, the Republic of Korea, and other
Asian countries and regions affected by the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Li admitted that construction of some real estate projects has
been delayed due to the lack of funds, and foreign investors are
now taking a more prudent attitude toward further investment.
</P>
<P>
"But this does not mean they will withdraw their funds," said
Li, adding that such a delay is somewhat conducive to reducing the
current oversupply in Pudong's real estate market.
</P>
<P>
Li said that projects funded by Japan and Singapore have
suffered the least, with most of them either being completed or
smoothly under way as planned. A residential building, financed by
Japan's Matsushita Electric Works and completed last September, is
30 percent occupied, according to him.
</P>
<P>
Despite severe financial difficulties at home, Republic of Korea
companies are still pressing forward with their projects
here. Some projects may have been delayed, but "that doesn't mean
they will be abandoned," said an official from ROK's Daewoo
Group.
</P>
<P>
Investors from Hong Kong and Taiwan continue to bring in
funds. The Shangri-la Hotel, funded by a Hong Kong company, is
being given the finishing touches preparatory to its expected
opening this October.
</P>
<P>
"Projects with investment from Thailand have suffered the
most," noted Li. Some planned projects now see no prospects of
starting, while some ongoing ones are likely to be
halted. However, investors are still keeping a close eye on
Pudong, Li added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
