<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinkel Says NATO Intervention in Kosovo Needs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 14 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
stressed on Sunday that any NATO military intervention in the
Serbian province of Kosovo must first be approved by the U.N.
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Sunday, Kinkel said that the planned
NATO aerial manoeuvres in Albania and the Republic of Macedonia on
Monday could go without U.N. mandate because it takes place in two
countries which have participated in the NATO program of
"Partnership for Peace" and which have given green light to the
exercise.
</P>
<P>
However, in case of a NATO military intervention in Kosovo or
its airspace, an approval by the U.N. Security Council was
required, Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
By contrast, U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen said
earlier that a U.N. approval of a NATO intervention in Kosovo was
"desirable, but not necessary".
</P>
<P>
German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe on Sunday also did not
rule out a NATO military action in Kosovo without preceding U.N.
approval.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin is due to meet Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic in Moscow on Tuesday to seek a
peaceful solution to the Kosovo conflict. According to the Russian
news agency Interfax, Yeltsin would reiterate his opposition to a
NATO military intervention.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
